# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: electronic-component
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] Some displays can show only digits or alphanumeric characters.
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] They are called **segment displays**, because they are composed of several segments that switch on and off to give appearance of desired glyph.
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] The segments are usually single LEDs or liquid crystals.
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] They are mostly used in digital watches and pocket calculators.
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] Common types are seven-segment displays which are used for numerals only, and alphanumeric fourteen-segment displays and sixteen-segment displays which can display numerals and Roman alphabet letters.
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] A **seven-segment display** is a display device for digits and some letters.
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] It is often used in a device to display numbers – for example in a digital clock or calculator.
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] To a lesser extent, but still common, it is used to display alphanumeric information.
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] Since a seven-segment display tends to be less expensive than a display that can better represent any character and even a graphic image such as a dot matrix display, the design choice to use a seven-segment display is a tradeoff to minimize cost over providing richer functionality.
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] Seven-segment representation of figures can be found in patents as early as 1903 (in U.S. patent 1,126,641), when Carl Kinsley invented a method of telegraphically transmitting letters and numbers and having them printed on tape in a segmented format.
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] Wood invented an 8-segment display, which displayed the number 4 using a diagonal bar (U.S. patent 974,943).
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] In 1910, a seven-segment display illuminated by incandescent bulbs was used on a power-plant boiler room signal panel.
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] They were also used to show the dialed telephone number to operators during the transition from manual to automatic telephone dialing.
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] They did not achieve widespread use until the advent of LEDs in the 1970s.
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] Some early seven-segment displays used incandescent filaments in an evacuated bulb; they are also known as numitrons.
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] A variation (minitrons) made use of an evacuated potted box.
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] Minitrons are filament segment displays that are housed in DIP (dual in-line package) packages like modern LED segment displays.
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] There were also segment displays that used small incandescent light bulbs instead of LEDs or incandescent filaments.
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] These worked similarly to modern LED segment displays.
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] Vacuum fluorescent display versions were also used in the 1970s.
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] 1970s) LED seven-segment displays had each digit built on a single die.
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] Some included magnifying lenses in the design to try to make the digits more legible.
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] Other designs used 1 or 2 dies for every segment of the display.
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] Liquid-crystal display (LCD) largely superseded LED seven-segment displays.
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] The shapes of elements in an LCD panel are arbitrary since they are formed on the display by photolithography, while LED segments tend to be simple rectangles, because they have to be physically moulded to shape, which makes it difficult to form more complex shapes.
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] However, the easy recognition of seven-segment displays, and the comparatively high visual contrast obtained by such displays relative to dot-matrix digits, makes seven-segment multiple-digit LCD screens very common on basic calculators.
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] Seven-segment displays have been recommended against for critical information (i.e. information that is dangerous to health or safety if misread) due to misreading if upside down or if segments are "stuck" on or off.
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] Backlit dot-matrix LCDs have largely superseded seven-segment displays on such equipment.
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] The seven-segment display has inspired type designers to produce typefaces reminiscent of that display (but more legible), such as New Alphabet, "DB LCD Temp", "ION B", etc.
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] The seven-segment pattern is sometimes used in posters or tags, where the user either applies color to pre-printed segments, or applies color through a seven-segment digit template, to compose figures such as product prices or telephone numbers.
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] For gasoline price totems and other large signs, electromechanical seven-segment displays made up of electromagnetically flipped light-reflecting segments are still commonly used.
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] A precursor to the 7-segment display in the 1950s through the 1970s was the cold-cathode, neon-lamp-like nixie tube.
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] Starting in 1970, RCA sold a display device known as the *Numitron* that used incandescent filaments arranged into a seven-segment display.
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] In USSR, the first electronic calculator "Vega", which was produced from 1964, contains 20 decimal digits with seven-segment electroluminescent display.
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] In a simple LED package, typically all of the cathodes (negative terminals) or all of the anodes (positive terminals) of the segment LEDs are connected and brought out to a common pin; this is referred to as a "common cathode" or "common anode" device.
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] Hence a 7 segment plus decimal point package will only require nine pins, though commercial products typically contain more pins, and/or spaces where pins would go, in order to match standard IC sockets.
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] Integrated displays also exist, with single or multiple digits.
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] Some of these integrated displays incorporate their own internal decoder, though most do not: each individual LED is brought out to a connecting pin as described.
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] Multiple-digit LED displays as used in pocket calculators and similar devices used multiplexed displays to reduce the number of I/O pins required to control the display.
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] For example, all the anodes of the A segments of each digit position would be connected together and to a driver circuit pin, while the cathodes of all segments for each digit would be connected.
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] In this manner an eight digit display with seven segments and a decimal point would require only 8 cathode drivers and 8 anode drivers, instead of sixty-four drivers and IC pins.
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] Often in pocket calculators the digit drive lines would be used to scan the keyboard as well, providing further savings; however, pressing multiple keys at once would produce odd results on the multiplexed display.
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] The seven segments are arranged as a rectangle, with two vertical segments on each side and one horizontal segment each at the top, middle, and bottom.
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] Often the rectangle is *oblique* (slanted), which may aid readability.
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] The seven elements of the display can be lit in different combinations to represent each of the Arabic numerals.
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] The individual segments are referred to by the letters "a" to "g", and an optional decimal point (an "eighth segment", referred to as DP) is sometimes used for the display of non-integer numbers.
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] A single byte can encode the full state of a seven-segment display, including the decimal point.
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] The most popular bit encodings are *gfedcba* and *abcdefg*.
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] In the *gfedcba* representation, a byte value of 0x06 would turn on segments "c" and "b", which would display a "1" ((1)).
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] The numerical digits 0 to 9 are the most common characters displayed on seven-segment displays.
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] In Unicode 13.0, 10 codepoints had been given for segmented digits 0–9 in the Symbols for Legacy Computing block, to replicate early computer fonts that included seven-segment versions of the digits.
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] The official reference shows the less-common four-segment "7" ((7*)).
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] The binary-coded decimal (BCD) 0 to 9 digit values require four binary bits to hold their values.
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] Since four bits (24) can hold 16 values, this means hexadecimal (hex) digits can be represented by four bits too.
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] Due to the limited number of segments in seven-segment displays, the hexadecimal digits B and D are displayed as lowercase letters to avoid confusion with 8 ((B)) and 0 ((D)) respectively.
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] The digit "6" must also be displayed with the topmost segment as (6) to avoid ambiguity with the letter "b" ((b)).
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] Early decoder ICs often produced unintuitive patterns or duplicates of digits for 10-15, as they were designed to use as few gates as possible and only required to produce 0-9.
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] Many letters of the Latin alphabet can be reasonably implemented on a seven-segment display.
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] Though not every letter is available, it is possible to create many useful words.
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] By careful choice of words, one can sometimes work around unavailable letters.
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] Uppercase letters "B", "I", "S", "Z", and "D" & "O" conflict with the common seven-segment representation of digits "8", "1", "5", "2", and "0" ((B), (I*), (S), (Z), (O)) respectively, and the lowercase letter "g" with digit "9" ((g*)).
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] Upper case I ((I)) could be put on the left (as lower-case L is shown here) but this is not often done.
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] Lowercase 'b' and 'q' are identical to the alternate numerical digits '6' and '9' ((b), (q)).
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] An **eight-segment display** is a type of display based on eight segments that can be turned on or off according to the font pattern to be produced.
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] One application was in the Sharp EL-8, an early electronic calculator.
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] The eight-segment display produces more rounded digits than a seven-segment display, yielding a more "script-like" output, with the trade-off that fewer possible alphabetic characters can be displayed because the bars *F* and *G* are merged (see table below).
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] An eight segment display can sometimes display alphabetic characters with less readability because the segments *F* and *G* are combined and the corners are rounded.
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] The asymmetrical layout of the elements produced a distinctive "handwritten" digit style, with a half-height "0".
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] A **nine-segment display** is a type of display based on nine segments that can be turned on or off according to the graphic pattern to be produced.
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] It is an extension of the more common seven-segment display, having an additional two diagonal or vertical segments (one between the top and the middle, and the other between the bottom and the horizontal segments).
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] It provides an efficient method of displaying alphanumeric characters.
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] The letters displayed by a nine-segment display are not consistently uppercase or lowercase in shape.
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] A common compromise is to use a lower-case "n" instead of "N".
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] Depending on the design of the display segments, the use of the extra two segments may be avoided whenever possible, as in the Nixxo X-Page "tall" lowercase "r" and "y".
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] In some Soviet digital calculators of the 1970s, such as the Elektronika 4-71b, 9-segment displays were used to provide basic alphanumerics and avoid confusions with representing numbers in Soviet postcodes.
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] The extra two bars were slanted forward, allowing for an appropriate-looking И, and to differentiate the numeral 3 from the letter З.
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] The Sharp Compet calculator also uses a 9-segment display, allowing a small range of characters and symbols to be used.
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] Nine-segment displays are used in many Timex digital watches, and some pagers, such as the Nixxo XPage, the Arch BR502 pager, and the Scope Geo N8T.
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] They are also used in some Epson Stylus printers, and Newport iSeries digital meters.
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] The display used in the iSeries is unique in that it has a vertical extra segment at top, and a fully backwards-leaning slant for the extra segment at bottom.
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] This allows for a somewhat more natural-appearing R and M.
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] Pinball tables produced by Bally from 1986 to 1989 used nine-segment scoring displays.
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] A nine-segment display has been developed for displaying Bengali and Roman numerals.
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] A **fourteen-segment display** (**FSD**), also known as a **starburst display** or **Union Jack display**, is a type of display based on 14 segments that can be turned on or off to produce letters and numerals.
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] It is an expansion of the more common seven-segment display, having an additional four diagonal and two vertical segments with the middle horizontal segment broken in half.
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] A seven-segment display suffices for numerals and certain letters, but unambiguously rendering the ISO basic Latin alphabet requires more detail.
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] A slight variation is the sixteen-segment display which allows additional legibility in displaying letters or other symbols.
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] A decimal point or comma may be present as an additional segment, or pair of segments; the comma (used for triple-digit groupings or as a decimal separator in many regions) is commonly formed by combining the decimal point with a closely 'attached' leftwards-descending arc-shaped segment.
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] Electronic alphanumeric displays may use LEDs, LCDs, or vacuum fluorescent display devices.
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] The LED variant is typically manufactured in single or dual character packages, allowing the system designer to choose the number of characters suiting the application.
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] Often a character generator is used to translate 7-bit ASCII character codes to the 14 bits that indicate which of the 14 segments to turn on or off.
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] By lighting different elements, different characters can be displayed.
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] In a 14-segment display, there is also an optional 15th segment which is a decimal point (denoted as "DP").
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] A 14-segment display is mostly used to display text because the 14 elements allow all Latin letters to be displayed both in upper case and lower case (with a few exceptions like "s").
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] Multiple-segment display devices use fewer elements than a full dot-matrix display, and may produce a better character appearance where the segments are shaped appropriately.
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] This can reduce power consumption and the number of driver components.
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] Fourteen-segment gas-plasma displays were used in pinball machines from 1986 through 1991 with an additional comma and period part making for a total of 16 segments.
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] Fourteen and sixteen-segment displays were used to produce alphanumeric characters on calculators and other embedded systems.
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] Applications today include displays fitted to telephone Caller ID units, gymnasium equipment, VCRs, car stereos, microwave ovens, slot machines, and DVD players.
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] Such displays were very common on pinball machines for displaying the score and other information, before the widespread use of dot-matrix display panels.
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] Multiple segment alphanumeric displays are nearly as old as the use of electricity.
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] A 1908 textbook describes an alphanumeric display system using incandescent lamps and a mechanical switching arrangement.
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] Each of 21 lamps was connected to a switch operated by a set of slotted bars, installed in a rotating drum.
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] This *commutator* assembly could be arranged so that as the drum was rotated, different sets of switches were closed and different letters and figures could be displayed.
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] The scheme would have been used for "talking" signs to spell out messages, but a complete set of commutator switches, drums and lamps would have been required for each letter of a message, making the resulting sign quite expensive.
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] A few different versions of the fourteen segment display exist as cold-cathode neon lamps.
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] For example, one type made by Burroughs Corporation was called "Panaplex".
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] Instead of using a filament as the incandescent versions do, these use a cathode charged to a 180 V potential which causes the electrified segment to glow a bright orange color.
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] A **sixteen-segment display** (**SISD**) is a type of display based on sixteen segments that can be turned on or off to produce a graphic pattern.
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] It is an extension of the more common seven-segment display, adding four diagonal and two vertical segments and splitting the three horizontal segments in half.
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] Other variants include the fourteen-segment display which does not split the top or bottom horizontal segments, and the twenty-two-segment display that allows lower-case characters with descenders.
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] Often a character generator is used to translate 7-bit ASCII character codes to the 16 bits that indicate which of the 16 segments to turn on or off.
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] Sixteen-segment displays were originally designed to display alphanumeric characters (Latin letters and Arabic digits).
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] Later they were used to display Thai numerals and Persian characters.
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] Non-electronic displays using this pattern existed as early as 1902.
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] Before the advent of inexpensive dot-matrix displays, sixteen and fourteen-segment displays were used to produce alphanumeric characters on calculators and other embedded systems.
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] Later they were used on videocassette recorders (VCR), DVD players, microwave ovens, car stereos, telephone Caller ID displays, and slot machines.
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] Sixteen-segment displays may be based on one of several technologies, the three most common optoelectronics types being LED, LCD and VFD.
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] The LED variant is typically manufactured in single or dual character packages, to be combined as needed into text line displays of a suitable length for the application in question; they can also be stacked to build multiline displays.
[src:electronic-component/7-segment] This way, a point or comma may be displayed between character positions instead of occupying a whole position by itself, which would be the case if employing the bottom middle vertical segment as a point and the bottom left diagonal segment as a comma.
[src:electronic-component/7400-series-integrated-circuits] The **7400 series** is a popular logic family of transistor–transistor logic (TTL) integrated circuits (ICs).
[src:electronic-component/7400-series-integrated-circuits] In 1964, Texas Instruments introduced the SN5400 series of logic chips, in a ceramic semiconductor package.
[src:electronic-component/7400-series-integrated-circuits] A low-cost plastic package SN7400 series was introduced in 1966 which quickly gained over 50% of the logic chip market, and eventually becoming *de facto* standardized electronic components.
[src:electronic-component/7400-series-integrated-circuits] Since the introduction of the original bipolar-transistor TTL parts, pin-compatible parts were introduced with such features as low-power CMOS technology and lower supply voltages.
[src:electronic-component/7400-series-integrated-circuits] Surface mount packages exist for several popular logic family functions.
[src:electronic-component/7400-series-integrated-circuits] The 7400 series contains hundreds of devices that provide everything from basic logic gates, flip-flops, and counters, to special purpose bus transceivers and arithmetic logic units (ALU).
[src:electronic-component/7400-series-integrated-circuits] Specific functions are described in a list of 7400 series integrated circuits.
[src:electronic-component/7400-series-integrated-circuits] Some TTL parts were made with an extended military-specification temperature range.
[src:electronic-component/7400-series-integrated-circuits] These parts are prefixed with **54** instead of **74** in the part number.
[src:electronic-component/7400-series-integrated-circuits] The less-common **64** and **84** prefixes on Texas Instruments parts indicated an industrial temperature range.
[src:electronic-component/7400-series-integrated-circuits] Since the 1970s, new product families have been released to replace the original 7400 series.
[src:electronic-component/7400-series-integrated-circuits] More recent TTL-compatible logic families were manufactured using CMOS or BiCMOS technology rather than TTL.
[src:electronic-component/7400-series-integrated-circuits] Today, surface-mounted CMOS versions of the 7400 series are used in various applications in electronics and for glue logic in computers and industrial electronics.
[src:electronic-component/7400-series-integrated-circuits] The original through-hole devices in dual in-line packages (DIP/DIL) were the mainstay of the industry for many decades.
[src:electronic-component/7400-series-integrated-circuits] They are useful for rapid breadboard-prototyping and for education and remain available from most manufacturers.
[src:electronic-component/7400-series-integrated-circuits] The fastest types and very low voltage versions are typically surface-mount only, however.
[src:electronic-component/7400-series-integrated-circuits] The first part number in the series, the 7400, is a 14-pin IC containing four two-input NAND gates.
[src:electronic-component/7400-series-integrated-circuits] Each gate uses two input pins and one output pin, with the remaining two pins being power (+5 V) and ground.
[src:electronic-component/7400-series-integrated-circuits] This part was made in various through-hole and surface-mount packages, including flat pack and plastic/ceramic dual in-line.
[src:electronic-component/7400-series-integrated-circuits] Additional characters in a part number identify the package and other variations.
[src:electronic-component/7400-series-integrated-circuits] Unlike the older resistor–transistor logic integrated circuits, bipolar TTL gates were unsuitable to be used as analog devices, providing low gain, poor stability, and low input impedance.
[src:electronic-component/7400-series-integrated-circuits] Special-purpose TTL devices were used to provide interface functions such as Schmitt triggers or monostable multivibrator timing circuits.
[src:electronic-component/7400-series-integrated-circuits] Inverting gates could be cascaded as a ring oscillator, useful for purposes where high stability was not required.
[src:electronic-component/7400-series-integrated-circuits] The 7400 quad 2-input NAND gate was the first product in the series, introduced by Texas Instruments in a military grade metal flat package (5400W) in October 1964.
[src:electronic-component/7400-series-integrated-circuits] The pin assignment of this early series differed from the *de facto* standard set by the later series in DIP packages (in particular, ground was connected to pin 11 and the power supply to pin 4, compared to pins 7 and 14 for DIP packages).
[src:electronic-component/7400-series-integrated-circuits] The extremely popular commercial grade plastic DIP (7400N) followed in the third quarter of 1966.
[src:electronic-component/7400-series-integrated-circuits] The 5400 and 7400 series were used in many popular minicomputers in the 1970s and early 1980s.
[src:electronic-component/7400-series-integrated-circuits] Some models of the DEC PDP-series "minis" used the 74181 ALU as the main computing element in the CPU.
[src:electronic-component/7400-series-integrated-circuits] Other examples were the Data General Nova series and Hewlett-Packard 21MX, 1000, and 3000 series.
[src:electronic-component/7400-series-integrated-circuits] In 1965, typical quantity-one pricing for the SN5400 (military grade, in ceramic welded flat-pack) was around 22 USD.
[src:electronic-component/7400-series-integrated-circuits] As of 2007, individual commercial-grade chips in molded epoxy (plastic) packages can be purchased for approximately US$0.25 each, depending on the particular chip.
[src:electronic-component/7400-series-integrated-circuits] 7400 series parts were constructed using bipolar junction transistors (BJT), forming what is referred to as transistor–transistor logic or **TTL**.
[src:electronic-component/7400-series-integrated-circuits] Newer series, more or less compatible in function and logic level with the original parts, use CMOS technology or a combination of the two (BiCMOS).
[src:electronic-component/7400-series-integrated-circuits] Originally the bipolar circuits provided higher speed but consumed more power than the competing 4000 series of CMOS devices.
[src:electronic-component/7400-series-integrated-circuits] Bipolar devices are also limited to a fixed power-supply voltage, typically 5 V, while CMOS parts often support a range of supply voltages.
[src:electronic-component/7400-series-integrated-circuits] Milspec-rated devices for use in extended temperature conditions are available as the 5400 series.
[src:electronic-component/7400-series-integrated-circuits] Texas Instruments also manufactured radiation-hardened devices with the prefix *RSN*, and the company offered beam-lead bare dies for integration into hybrid circuits with a *BL* prefix designation.
[src:electronic-component/7400-series-integrated-circuits] Regular-speed TTL parts were also available for a time in the 6400 series – these had an extended industrial temperature range of −40 °C to +85 °C.
[src:electronic-component/7400-series-integrated-circuits] While companies such as Mullard listed 6400-series compatible parts in 1970 data sheets, by 1973 there was no mention of the 6400 family in the Texas Instruments *TTL Data Book*.
[src:electronic-component/7400-series-integrated-circuits] Texas Instruments brought back the 6400 series in 1989 for the SN64BCT540.
[src:electronic-component/7400-series-integrated-circuits] The SN64BCTxxx series is still in production as of 2023.
[src:electronic-component/7400-series-integrated-circuits] Some companies have also offered industrial extended temperature range variants using the regular 7400-series part numbers with a prefix or suffix to indicate the temperature grade.
[src:electronic-component/7400-series-integrated-circuits] As integrated circuits in the 7400 series were made in different technologies, usually compatibility was retained with the original TTL logic levels and power-supply voltages.
[src:electronic-component/7400-series-integrated-circuits] An integrated circuit made in CMOS is not a TTL chip, since it uses field-effect transistors (FETs) and not bipolar junction transistors (BJT), but similar part numbers are retained to identify similar logic functions and electrical (power and I/O voltage) compatibility in the different subfamilies.
[src:electronic-component/7400-series-integrated-circuits] Over 40 different logic subfamilies use this standardized part number scheme.
[src:electronic-component/7400-series-integrated-circuits] The headings in the following table are: *V*cc – power-supply voltage; *t*pd – maximum gate delay; *I*OL – maximum output current at low level; *I*OH – maximum output current at high level; *t*pd, *I*OL, and *I*OH apply to most gates in a given family.
[src:electronic-component/7400-series-integrated-circuits] Driver or buffer gates have higher output currents.
[src:electronic-component/7400-series-integrated-circuits] Parameters are shown for the 2-input NAND gate (74x00 or 74x1G00) at *V*cc = 5 V,Ta = 25 °C, CL = 50 pF.
[src:electronic-component/7400-series-integrated-circuits] The letter "U" when added to the family code (e.g.
[src:electronic-component/7400-series-integrated-circuits] 74HCU) indicates an unbuffered CMOS circuit.
[src:electronic-component/7400-series-integrated-circuits] Typically, there is only one unbuffered circuit in a family: the hex inverter (74x04).
[src:electronic-component/7400-series-integrated-circuits] Unbuffered circuits are intended for analogue applications such as crystal oscillators.
[src:electronic-component/7400-series-integrated-circuits] The letter "H" when added to the family code (e.g.
[src:electronic-component/7400-series-integrated-circuits] 74LVCH) indicates a circuit with a bus-hold feature.
[src:electronic-component/7400-series-integrated-circuits] That is, if the input bus goes to a high-impendance or floating state then the outputs keep their state according to the last valid input state.
[src:electronic-component/7400-series-integrated-circuits] This eliminates the need for pull-up resistors or pull-down resistors.
[src:electronic-component/7400-series-integrated-circuits] The letter "R" when added to the family code (e.g.
[src:electronic-component/7400-series-integrated-circuits] 74LCXR) indicates a circuit with integrated resistors at the outputs in order to reduce overshoot and undershoot of the output signal.
[src:electronic-component/7400-series-integrated-circuits] Parameters are shown for the 2-input NAND gate (74x00 or 74x1G00) at Vcc = 3.3 V,Ta = 25 °C, CL = 50 pF.
[src:electronic-component/7400-series-integrated-circuits] The letter "Z" when added to the family code (e.g.
[src:electronic-component/7400-series-integrated-circuits] 74LVTZ) indicates a circuit where a high-impedance state of all outputs is guaranteed when the power supply voltage drops below a certain threshold.
[src:electronic-component/7400-series-integrated-circuits] There are no simple gates in these families.
[src:electronic-component/7400-series-integrated-circuits] Parameters are for a transceiver (74x245, 74x16245, or similar).
[src:electronic-component/7400-series-integrated-circuits] B-side outputs are all open-collector in this family.
[src:electronic-component/7400-series-integrated-circuits] Many parts in the CMOS HC, AC, AHC, and VHC families are also offered in "T" versions (HCT, ACT, AHCT and VHCT) which have input thresholds that are compatible with both TTL and 3.3 V CMOS signals.
[src:electronic-component/7400-series-integrated-circuits] The non-T parts have conventional CMOS input thresholds, which are more restrictive than TTL thresholds.
[src:electronic-component/7400-series-integrated-circuits] Typically, CMOS input thresholds require high-level signals to be at least 70% of Vcc and low-level signals to be at most 30% of Vcc.
[src:electronic-component/7400-series-integrated-circuits] The 74H family is the same basic design as the 7400 family with resistor values reduced.
[src:electronic-component/7400-series-integrated-circuits] This reduced the typical propagation delay from 9 ns to 6 ns but increased the power consumption.
[src:electronic-component/7400-series-integrated-circuits] The 74H family provided a number of unique devices for CPU designs in the 1970s.
[src:electronic-component/7400-series-integrated-circuits] Many designers of military and aerospace equipment used this family over a long period and as they need exact replacements, this family is still produced by Lansdale Semiconductor.
[src:electronic-component/7400-series-integrated-circuits] The 74S family, using Schottky circuitry, uses more power than the 74, but is faster.
[src:electronic-component/7400-series-integrated-circuits] The 74LS family of ICs is a lower-power version of the 74S family, with slightly higher speed but lower power dissipation than the original 74 family; it became the most popular variant once it was widely available.
[src:electronic-component/7400-series-integrated-circuits] Many 74LS ICs can be found in microcomputers and digital consumer electronics manufactured in the 1980s and early 1990s.
[src:electronic-component/7400-series-integrated-circuits] The 74F family was introduced by Fairchild Semiconductor and adopted by other manufacturers; it is faster than the 74, 74LS and 74S families.
[src:electronic-component/7400-series-integrated-circuits] Through the late 1980s and 1990s newer versions of this family were introduced to support the lower operating voltages used in newer CPU devices.
[src:electronic-component/7400-series-integrated-circuits] Part number schemes varied by manufacturer.
[src:electronic-component/7400-series-integrated-circuits] Many logic families maintain a consistent use of the device numbers as an aid to designers.
[src:electronic-component/7400-series-integrated-circuits] Some manufacturers, such as Mullard and Siemens, had pin-compatible TTL parts, but with a completely different numbering scheme; however, data sheets identified the *7400-compatible* number as an aid to recognition.
[src:electronic-component/7400-series-integrated-circuits] At the time the 7400 series was being made, some European manufacturers (that traditionally followed the Pro Electron naming convention), such as Philips/Mullard, produced a series of TTL integrated circuits with part names beginning with FJ.
[src:electronic-component/7400-series-integrated-circuits] Another peculiarity of the Soviet-made 7400 series was the packaging material used in the 1970s–1980s.
[src:electronic-component/7400-series-integrated-circuits] Instead of the ubiquitous black resin, they had a brownish-green body colour with subtle swirl marks created during the moulding process.
[src:electronic-component/7400-series-integrated-circuits] It was jokingly referred to in the Eastern Bloc electronics industry as the "elephant-dung packaging", due to its appearance.
[src:electronic-component/7400-series-integrated-circuits] Before July 1974 the two letters from the functional description were inserted after the first digit of the series.
[src:electronic-component/7400-series-integrated-circuits] A number of different technologies were available from the Soviet Union, Czechoslovakia, Poland, and East Germany.
[src:electronic-component/7400-series-integrated-circuits] The 8400 series in the table below indicates an industrial temperature range from −25 °C to +85 °C (as opposed to −40 °C to +85 °C for the 6400 series).
[src:electronic-component/7400-series-integrated-circuits] Around 1990 the production of standard logic ceased in all Eastern European countries except the Soviet Union and later Russia and Belarus.
[src:electronic-component/7400-series-integrated-circuits] The Russian company Angstrem manufactures 54HC circuits as the 5514БЦ1 series, 54AC as the 5514БЦ2 series, and 54LVC as the 5524БЦ2 series.
[src:electronic-component/7400-series-integrated-circuits] As of 2024, the 133, 136, and 1533 series are in production at Kvazar Kyiv in Ukraine.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Plugs and sockets may sometimes combine male and female contacts.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Plugs and wall-mounted sockets for portable appliances became available in the 1880s, to replace connections to light sockets.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] A proliferation of types were subsequently developed for both convenience and protection from electrical injury.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Electrical plugs and sockets differ from one another in voltage and current rating, shape, size, and connector type.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Different standard systems of plugs and sockets are used around the world, and many obsolete socket types are still found in older buildings.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Coordination of technical standards has allowed some types of plug to be used across large regions to facilitate the production and import of electrical appliances and for the convenience of travellers.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Some multi-standard sockets allow use of several types of plug.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Incompatible sockets and plugs may be used with the help of adaptors, though these may not always provide full safety and performance.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Single-phase sockets have receptacles for two power pins, one to carry the electrical current from the power source to the connected device (called *live*, *line*, or *phase pin*) and another one to carry it back to the power source (called *neutral pin*).
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Many sockets have a third receptacle or pin for a safety connection to earth ground.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] The plug is a *male* connector, usually with protruding pins that match the receptacles (*female* contacts) in a socket.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Some plugs also have a female contact, used only for the earth ground connection.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Typically no energy is supplied to any exposed pins or terminals on the socket, hence the power pins are always part of the plug rather than the socket.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] In addition to the recessed contacts of the energised socket, plug and socket systems often have other safety features to reduce the risk of electric shock or damage to appliances.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] When commercial electric power was first introduced in the 1880s, it was used primarily for lighting.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Other portable appliances (such as vacuum cleaners, electric fans, smoothing irons, and curling-tong heaters) were connected to light-bulb sockets.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] As early as 1885 a two-pin plug and wall socket format was available on the British market.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] By about 1910 the first three-pin earthed (grounded) plugs appeared.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Over time other safety improvements were gradually introduced to the market.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] One of the first national standards for plugs and wall sockets was enacted in 1915 in the UK.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Designs of plugs and sockets have gradually developed to reduce the risk of electric shock and fire.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Plugs are shaped to prevent bodily contact with live parts.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Sockets may be recessed and plugs designed to fit closely within the recess to reduce risk of a user contacting the live pins.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Contact pins may be sheathed with insulation over part of their length, so as to reduce exposure of energized metal during insertion or removal of the plug.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Sockets may have automatic shutters to stop foreign objects from being inserted into energized contacts.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Sockets are often set into a surround which prevents accidental contact with the live wires in the wall behind it.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Some also have an integrated cover (e.g. a hinged flap) covering the socket itself when not in use, or a switch to turn off the socket.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Some plugs, particularly the British Type G, have a built-in fuse which breaks the circuit if too much current flows.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] A third contact for a connection to earth is intended to protect against insulation failure of the connected device.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Some early unearthed plug and socket types were revised to include an earthing pin or phased out in favour of earthed types.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] The plug is often designed so that the earth ground contact connects before the energized circuit contacts.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] The assigned IEC appliance class is governed by the requirement for earthing or equivalent protection.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Class I equipment requires an earth contact in the plug and socket, while Class II equipment is unearthed and protects the user with double insulation.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Where a "neutral" conductor exists in supply wiring, polarization of the plug can improve safety by preserving the distinction in the equipment.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] For example, appliances may ensure that switches interrupt the live side of the circuit, or can connect the shell of a screw-base lampholder to neutral to reduce electric shock hazard.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] In some designs, polarized plugs cannot be mated with non-polarized sockets.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] In most NEMA 1 plugs, for example, the neutral blade is slightly wider than the hot blade, so it can only be inserted one way.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Wiring systems where both circuit conductors have a significant potential with respect to earth do not benefit from polarized plugs.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Plugs and power cords have a rated voltage and current assigned to them by the manufacturer.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Using a plug or power cord that is inappropriate for the load may be a safety hazard.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] For example, high-current equipment can cause a fire when plugged into an extension cord with a current rating lower than necessary.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Sometimes the cords used to plug in dual voltage 120 V / 240 V equipment are rated only for 125 V, so care must be taken by travellers to use only cords with an appropriate voltage rating.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Various methods can be used to increase the number or reach of sockets.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Extension cords (extension leads) are used for temporary connections when a socket is not within convenient reach of an appliance's power lead.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] This may be in the form of a single socket on a flexible cable or a power strip with multiple sockets.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] A power strip may also have switches, surge voltage protection, or overcurrent protection.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Multisocket adaptors (or "splitters") allow the connection of two or more plugs to a single socket.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] They are manufactured in various configurations, depending on the country and the region in which they are used, with various ratings.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] This allows connecting more than one electrical consumer item to one single socket and is mainly used for low power devices (TV sets, table lamps, computers, etc.).
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] They are usually rated for 6 A, 10 A, or 16 A at 250 V or for 15 A or less at 125 V.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] In some countries such adaptors are banned and are not available in shops, as they may lead to fires due to overloading them or can cause excessive mechanical stress to wall-mounted sockets.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Adaptors can be made with ceramic, Bakelite, or other plastic bodies.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] but is intended to accept a number of different plug types.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Old Chinese dual socket accepting both unearthed two-pin (upper) and earthed three-pin (lower) plugs.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] "Hybrid", "multi-standard", or "universal" sockets are intended to accommodate plugs of two or more types.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] In some jurisdictions, they violate safety standards for sockets.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Safety advocates, the United States Army, and a manufacturer of sockets point out a number of safety issues with universal socket and adaptors, including voltage mismatch, exposure of live pins, lack of proper earth ground connection, or lack of protection from overload or short circuit.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Universal sockets may not meet technical standards for durability, plug retention force, temperature rise of components, or other performance requirements, as they are outside the scope of national and international technical standards.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] A technical standard may include compatibility of a socket with more than one form of plug.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] The Thai dual socket is specified in figure 4 of TIS 166-2549 and is designed to accept Thai plugs, and also Type A, B, and C plugs.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Chinese dual sockets have both an unearthed socket that accepts A and C plugs and an earthed socket that accepts Type I plugs.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Since the 2021 revision of the Chinese standard, the installation of such dual sockets is no longer allowed in China, but they can still be found in many existing installations.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Such Thai or Chinese dual sockets also accept plugs normally fitted to 120 V appliances (e.g.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] 120 V rated NEMA 1-15 ungrounded plugs).
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] This can cause an electrical incompatibility, since both countries supply residential power at 220–230 V.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] These dual sockets also accept French and Schuko plugs (Types E and F), but unsafely: no earth contact is established and live pins may be exposed when a plug is partially inserted.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Commonly, manufacturers provide an IEC 60320 inlet on an appliance, with a detachable power cord (mains flex lead) and appropriate plug in order to avoid manufacturing whole appliances, with the only difference being the type of plug.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Alternatively, the plug itself can often be swappable using standard or proprietary connectors.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Adaptors between standards are not included in most standards, and as a result they have no formal quality criteria defined.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Physical compatibility does not ensure that the appliance and socket match in frequency or voltage.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Adaptors allow travellers to connect devices to foreign sockets, but do not change voltage or frequency.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] A voltage converter is required for electrical compatibility in places with a different voltage than the device is designed for.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Mismatch in frequency between supply and appliances may still cause problems even at the correct voltage.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Some appliances have a switch for the selection of voltage.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Many modern devices use AC adapters that accept 100–240 V voltage at 50 or 60 Hz, meaning they can be used anywhere in the world as long as a suitable plug adapter is used.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plugs and sockets used in a given area are regulated by local governments.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC) maintains a guide with letter designations for generally compatible types of plugs, which expands on earlier guides published by the United States Department of Commerce.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This is a *de facto* naming standard and guide to travellers.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Some letter types correspond to several current ratings or different technical standards, so the letter does not uniquely identify a plug and socket within the type family, nor guarantee compatibility.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Physical compatibility of the plug and socket does not ensure correct voltage, frequency, or current capacity.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Not all plug and socket families have letters in the IEC guide, but those that have are noted in this article, as are some additional letters commonly used by retail vendors.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Europe, CENELEC publishes a list of approved plug and socket technical standards used in the member countries.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] A number of countries in Oceania as well as China and Argentina use a plug that has two flat pins at an angle, forming a V-shape, as well as a flat vertical grounding pin.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] While the exact pin dimensions and the polarity vary between different countries, these plugs and sockets are all compatible with each other and are known as *Type I*.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug and socket system used in Argentina is defined by several standards of the Argentine Normalization and Certification Institute (IRAM).
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] IRAM 2071 defines two sockets that have the same form factor, but differ in size and rating.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The smaller, more common socket is rated for 10 A.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The larger variant, rated for 20 A, is mostly used for higher-power appliances such as air conditioners.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] IRAM 2073 defines the corresponding plugs used for Class I appliances (that require earthing).
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug and socket system has an earthing pin and two flat current-carrying pins forming an inverted V-shape (120°).
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The power pins are set at 30° to the vertical with a distance of 7.92 mm (0.312 in) from their centres to the centre of the plug; they are 18.2 mm (0.717 in) long.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The earthing pin is 21.4 mm (0.843 in) long and placed below the plug centre at a distance of 10.31 mm (0.406 in).
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The pins of the 20 A version are larger – 8.0 by 1.9 mm (0.315 by 0.075 in) – and placed further away from the centre of the plug – 9.53 mm (0.375 in) for the power pins, 11.1 mm (0.437 in) for the earthing pin.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] At 21.8 mm (0.858 in), the earthing pin is a bit longer, while the power pins are a bit shorter at 17.8 mm (0.701 in).
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There is also an unearthed version of the 10 A plug, defined by IRAM 2063, that lacks an earthing pin and can be used with Class II appliances.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] 20 A plugs, on the other hand, must always provide earthing.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Insulating sleeves around the upper parts of the power pins are allowed, but not required.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] When used, they significantly reduce the risk of electric shock from accidentally touching the pins of a partially inserted plug.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Because the pins of the 20 A plug are placed farther apart than those of the 10 A plug, the two Argentine plug types are mutually incompatible.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It is not possible to insert a 20 A plug into a 10 A socket or vice versa.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The most important difference from the Australasian and Chinese plugs is that the Argentine plug is wired with the live and neutral contacts reversed.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Argentina, when the earth contact is positioned downward, the live (line) contact is on the right side of the socket, while in Australasia and China it is on the left (assuming the same orientation).
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Brazil, Type I–style plugs and sockets are still commonly used in old installations for high-power appliances like air conditioners, dishwashers, and household ovens.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] These are often called "Argentine plugs" and are indeed physically identical to the IRAM plugs rated for 20 A, though they might have been developed independently on the basis of the American NEMA 10-20 standard (which uses the same form factor).
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] While these plugs are sometimes used for normal single-phase power and wired in the same way as in Argentina, some are wired for split-phase power with two "hot" (or phase) wires and a neutral wire, but no earth connection.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Care must therefore be taken that the same wiring scheme is used in the socket and in the plug, since otherwise the equipment would surely be damaged.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In newer installations, the 20 A version of the Type N plug, adopted by Brazil as national standard NBR 14136, is generally preferred.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This Australian/New Zealand standard is used in Australia, New Zealand, Fiji, Tonga, Solomon Islands, and Papua New Guinea.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug shape and basic dimensions are identical to the 10 A plug used in Argentina.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Australasian standard defines a series of plugs and sockets for devices drawing up to 10, 15, 20, 25 and 32 A that are one-way compatible.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] All sockets accept plugs of equal or lower current ratings, but not higher.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] For example, a 10 A plug will fit all sockets but a 20 A plug will fit only 20, 25 and 32 A sockets.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The three flat pins all measure 6.35 by 1.63 mm (0.250 by 0.064 in) – very slightly larger than in Argentina.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The length of the power pins is 17.06 mm (0.672 in), while the earthing pin has a length of 19.94 mm (0.785 in) – somewhat shorter than in Argentina.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In the 15 A plug, the height of the earth pin is increased from 6.35 to 9.08 mm (0.357 in), while the dimensions of the power pins remain the same.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In the 20 A plug, however, their height is increased in the same way, so that the surface dimensions of the three pins are again identical.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In the 25 A version, the earthing pin takes the shape of an inverted L (an extra bar is added at the top end), and in the 32 A version it takes the shape of a sideways U (extra bars are added at both ends).
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In general, only 10 A and 15 A socket outlets are likely to be encountered in domestic or commercial installations.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] 20 A sockets are rare and higher rated ones are very rare.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] An unearthed version of the 10 A plug with two angled power pins but no earthing pin is used with double-insulated appliances, but sockets and higher-rated plugs always include an earth contact.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In New Zealand, PDL 940 "tap-on" or "piggy-back" plugs are available which allow a second 10 A plug to be fitted to the rear of the plug.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Australia these piggy-back plugs are now available only on pre-made extension leads.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] A novel feature of modern Australian socket outlets is a snap-fitting surround for the socket, covering the screws that affix the socket to the wall, and extending all the way around the socket periphery.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Australia's standard plug/socket system was originally codified as standard C112 (floated provisionally in 1937, and adopted as a formal standard in 1938), which was based on a design patented by Harvey Hubbell and was superseded by AS 3112 in 1990.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The requirement for insulated pins was introduced in the 2000 revision, and became effective 5 years after its publication.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The standard for Mainland Chinese plugs and sockets (excluding Hong Kong and Macau) is set out in GB 2099.1 and GB 1002.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] As part of China's commitment for entry into the WTO, the new CPCS (Compulsory Product Certification System) has been introduced, and compliant Chinese plugs have been awarded the CCC Mark by this system.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plugs are three-wire, earthed, rated for 10 or 16 A, 250 V, and are chiefly used for Class I applications.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The pins of the 10 A version are 1.55 mm (0.061 in) thick by 6.4 mm (0.252 in) wide; the centres of the power pins are placed 7.9 mm (0.311 in) from the plug centre, while the centre of the earth pin is 10.3 mm (0.406 in) away.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In both plug types, the live and neutral pins are 18 mm (0.709 in) long, while the earth pin is 21 mm (0.827 in) long.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This makes the 10 A version compatible with Argentine and Australasian 10 A sockets, as their dimensions are nearly identical.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Except for the pin length, all dimensions of the 16 A version are slightly larger.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Its pins are 1.8 by 8.1 mm (0.071 by 0.319 in); the centres of the power pins are placed 9.5 mm (0.374 in) from the plug centre, while the centre of the earth pin is 11.1 mm (0.437 in) away.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This makes this plug compatible with the 20 A sockets used in Argentina.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It is, however, incompatible with Chinese 10 A sockets as well as all Australasian sockets because of the different pin spacing.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Some sockets in China include a physical lockout preventing access to the active and neutral terminals unless an earth pin (which is slightly longer than the other two pins) is entered first; others require pins to be inserted into both live terminals to open the shutter.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Since its 2024 revision, GB 1002 also defines unearthed two-pin Class II plugs, though such plugs cannot be inserted into sockets that require an earth pin to open the shutters.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Already since 2008 for 16 A, and since 2021 also for 10 A, there is an unearthed Class II plug variant that uses an unwired dummy earth pin to open the shutters; unearthed plugs of this kind fit into all Chinese sockets of the same rating.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] China also uses American/Japanese NEMA 1-15 sockets and plugs for Class II appliances (however, polarized plugs with one prong wider than the other are not accepted).
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Older versions of GB 1002 also defined a socket type that accepts Europlugs (Type C), but this hybrid socket was removed from the 2021 revision of the standard.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The voltage at a Chinese socket of any type is 220 V.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In China, sockets typically have the earth contact above the power pins, while in Argentina and Australasia it is usually positioned below them.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] While Australasian plugs have insulating sleeves around the upper part of their power pins, that is not the case for most existing Chinese plugs, hence their pins may become live while there is still a large enough gap between the faces of the plug and socket to allow a finger to touch the pin.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Since 2022, insulating sleeves are also allowed on plugs sold in China; they will be mandatory from 2027.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The polarity of all grounded British sockets is standardized: earth is at the top and live is at the right of the socket.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This convention is also followed in other countries using these plugs and sockets.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] BS 546, "Two-pole and earthing-pin plugs, socket-outlets and socket-outlet adaptors for AC (50-60 Hz) circuits up to 250 V" describes four sizes of plug rated at 2 A, 5 A (Type D), 15 A (Type M) and 30 A.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plugs have three round pins arranged in a triangle, with the larger top pin being the earthing pin.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Plugs are non-interchangeable between current ratings.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Introduced in 1934, the BS 546 type has mostly been displaced in the UK by the BS 1363 standard.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] According to the IEC, some 40 countries use Type D (among them India) and about 15 countries use Type M.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] BS 1363 "13 A plugs, socket-outlets, adaptors and connection units" is the main plug and socket type used in the United Kingdom.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] According to the IEC it is also used in over 50 countries worldwide.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Some of these countries have national standards based on BS 1363, including Bahrain, Hong Kong, Ireland, Cyprus, Macau, Malaysia, Malta, Saudi Arabia, Singapore, Brunei, Sri Lanka, and the UAE.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This plug has three rectangular pins forming an isosceles triangle.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The BS 1363 plug has a fuse rated to protect its flexible cord from overload and consequent fire risk.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Modern appliances may only be sold with a fuse of the appropriate size pre-installed.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The United Kingdom, Ireland, and Malta use the BS 4573 two-pin plug and socket for electric shavers and toothbrushes.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug has insulating sleeves on the pins.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Although similar to the Europlug Type C, the diameter and spacing of the pins are slightly different and hence it will not fit into a Schuko socket.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There are, however, two-pin sockets and adaptors which will accept both BS 4573 and Europlugs.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The **CEE 7** standard is a set of general specifications and standard sheets for AC plugs and sockets, first created by the IECEE standards body in 1951.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] They are now the main system in use in most of Europe.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CEE 7 incorporates the two round pinned (with centres spaced at 19 mm) Schuko or Type F plug that was patented by Siemens-Schuckertwerke in 1929, and also the Type E plug, likely developed in Belgium around 1930 but never patented, therefore adopted by Czecho­slovakia, Poland and France.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CEE 7 have also developed and incorporated "universal" plugs that will work on both Type E and Type F sockets such as the Europlug.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] European countries (whether EU or non-EU) each have their own regulations and national standards; for example, some require child-resistant shutters, while others do not.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CE marking is neither applicable nor permitted on plugs and sockets.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The CEE 7 system has been adapted in many countries outside of Europe as well.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CEE 7/1 sockets and CEE 7/2 plugs are 2-pole connectors rated 10/16 A up to 250 V, with 4.8 by 19 mm (0.189 by 0.748 in) pins.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It has no protective earth and therefore poses a risk of electric shock due to missing circular recess.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Their sale or use has been banned in a number of countries.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The CEE 7/3 socket and CEE 7/4 plug are commonly called *Schuko*, an abbreviation for *Schutzkontakt*, *Protective contact* to earth ("Schuko" itself is a registered trademark of a German association established to own the term).
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The socket has a circular recess with two round holes and two earthing clips that engage before live pin contact is made.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Schuko system is unpolarized, allowing live and neutral to be reversed.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug is used in most European countries and on other continents, including in South Korea and Uruguay.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The European countries not using it at all are Belgium, Czech Republic, Cyprus, Ireland, Liechtenstein, Malta, Switzerland, and the United Kingdom; those not using it predominantly are Denmark, Faroe Islands, France, Italy, Monaco, San Marino, and Slovakia.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This electrical connector most likely originated in Belgium, where it was introduced in the 1930s by Vynckier Frères as well as Niko.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The CEE 7/5 socket and CEE 7/6 plug are defined in several national standards, among them the Belgian NBN C 61‑112, the French NF C 61-314, and the Czech ČSN 35 4516.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The CEE 7/5 socket is in Europe the primary standard of Belgium, Czechia, France, Poland, and Slovakia.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Denmark including the Faroe Islands and Greenland, both CEE 7/3 and CEE 7/5 are nowadays explicitly allowed alongside Type K.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The socket has a circular recess with two round holes.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The round earth pin projecting from the socket connects before the energized contacts touch.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The earth pin is centred between the apertures, offset by 10 mm (0.394 in).
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug has two round pins measuring 4.8 by 19 mm (0.189 by 0.748 in), spaced 19 mm (0.748 in) apart and with an aperture for the socket's projecting earth pin.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CEE 7/7 plugs have been designed to solve this incompatibility by being able to fit in either type of socket.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug is rated at 16 A and looks similar to CEE 7/4 plugs, but with earth contacts to fit both CEE 7/5 and CEE 7/3 sockets.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Due to its compatibility with the inherently unpolarized Schuko (CEE 7/4) plugs, appliances using it cannot expect the current to flow in any particular direction.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The CEE 7/16 Alternative I unearthed plug is used for unearthed appliances.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Alternative I is a round plug with cutouts to make it compatible with CEE 7/3 and CEE 7/5 sockets.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] (The similar-appearing CEE 7/17 has larger pins and a higher current rating.) This alternative is seldom used.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Alternative II, popularly known as the Europlug, is a flat 2.5 A-rated plug with two round 4 by 19 mm (0.157 by 0.748 in) pins, defined by Cenelec standard EN 50075 and national equivalents.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Europlug is not rewirable and must be supplied with a flexible cord.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It can be inserted in either direction, so live and neutral are connected arbitrarily.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] To improve contact with socket parts the Europlug has slightly flexible pins which converge toward their free ends.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Europlug is widely used in most of Europe and parts of the Middle East, Africa, South America, and Asia.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There is no socket defined to accept only the Europlug.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Instead, it fits a range of sockets including all three CEE 7 sockets (unearthed, German/"Schuko", and Belgian/French) and also many non-CEE 7 standard sockets such as Swiss, Danish and Italian (10 A) ones as well as Israeli sockets.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] British shaver sockets also accept Europlugs, although in this configuration the connection supply is only rated at 200 mA.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This is a round plug compatible with all three types of CEE 7 sockets.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Also called the "contour plug", it has two round pins measuring 4.8 by 19 mm (0.189 by 0.748 in).
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The pins are not sheathed, in contrast to e.g.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This Danish standard plug is described in the Danish Plug Equipment Section 107-2-D1 Standard sheet (SRAF1962/DB 16/87 DN10A-R).
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Like in most European plugs, the power pins of Danish plugs are 19 mm (0.75 in) long and spaced 19 mm (0.75 in) apart, with a diameter of 4.8 mm (0.19 in).
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The earthing pin is part of the plug (in contrast to French and Schuko plugs); it is D-shaped, 14 mm (0.55 in) long, and offset from the power pins by 13 mm (0.51 in).
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It is 4 mm (0.16 in) thick with a diameter of 6.5 mm (0.26 in).
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Danish standard provides for sockets to have child-resistant shutters.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Sockets are polarized in the same way as British ones: if earth is at the bottom, live is at the left of the socket.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Europlugs (CEE 7/16) and contour plugs (CEE 7/17) can safely be used with Danish sockets.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Physically the sockets also accept earthed CEE 7/4 (Schuko), CEE 7/6 (French), and CEE 7/7 (Schuko-French hybrid) plugs, but no earth connection will be established.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Therefore news sites and industry magazines warn that plugging these directly into a Type K socket can give noticeable electric shocks, be dangerous and even be life-threatening.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Traditionally all Danish sockets were equipped with a switch to prevent touching live pins when connecting/disconnecting the plug.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Today, sockets without switch are allowed, but they must be recessed to prevent touching the live pins.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Since the early 1990s earthed sockets have been required in all new electric installations in Denmark.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Older sockets need not be earthed, but all sockets, including old installations, must be protected by earth-fault interrupters by 1 July 2008.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] A variation (standard DK 2-5a) of the Danish plug is for use only on surge protected computer sockets.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It fits into the corresponding computer socket and the normal socket, but normal plugs deliberately do not fit into the special computer socket.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug is often used in companies, but rarely in private homes.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There is another variation for hospital equipment with a rectangular left pin, which is used for life support equipment.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In 1986, the International Electrotechnical Commission published IEC 60906-1, a specification for a plug and socket that look similar, but are not identical, to the Swiss plug and socket.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This standard was intended to one day become common for all of Europe and other regions with 230 V mains, but the effort to adopt it as a European Union standard was put on hold in the mid-1990s.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug and socket are rated 16 A 250 V AC and are intended for use only on systems having nominal voltages between 200 V and 250 V AC.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug pins are 4.5 mm in diameter, live and neutral are on centres 19 mm apart.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The live pin is on the right when looking at a socket with the earth pin offset up.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Shutters over the live and neutral pins are mandatory.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The first country to have officially adopted the standard is South Africa (as SANS 164-2).
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Paraguay has also adopted it as national standard (PNA-IEC 60906-1), but so far its application is voluntary, and as of March 2025, there is no indication that sockets of this type are commonly installed in the country.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Brazil developed a plug resembling IEC 60906-1 as the national standard under specification NBR 14136.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The NBR 14136 standard has two versions, neither of which has pin dimensions or ratings complying with IEC 60906-1.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Use at 127 V is permitted by NBR 14136, which is against the intention of IEC 60906-1.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] South Africa adopted IEC 60906-1 as its national standard, SANS 164-2, in 1992.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The standard specifies both a 2-pin unearthed and 3-pin earthed plug system, equivalent to IEC Type N.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] SANS 164-2 was designated the "preferred standard" in 2013, and South Africa is in the process of transitioning to it as the dominant system, expected to be completed by 2025 to 2035.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The SANS 164-2 system is compatible with the SANS 164-5 Europlug, commonly used in the country.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This transition aims to improve electrical safety and standardization, aligning South Africa with international plug and socket systems.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Brazil, which had been using mostly Europlugs as well as NEMA 1-15 and NEMA 5-15 plugs, adopted a (non-compliant) variant of IEC 60906-1 as the national standard in 1998 under specification NBR 14136 (revised in 2002).
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] These are used for both 220-volt and 127-volt regions of the country, despite the IEC 60906-2 recommendation that NEMA 5-15 be used for 120 V connections.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There are two types of sockets and plugs in NBR 14136: one for 10 A, with a 4.0 mm pin diameter, and another for 20 A, with a 4.8 mm pin diameter.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This differs from IEC 60906-1 which specifies a pin diameter of 4.5 mm and a rating of 16 A.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] NBR 14136 does not require shutters on the apertures, a further aspect of non-compliance with IEC 60906-1.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] NBR 14136 was not enforced in that country until 2007, when its adoption was made optional for manufacturers.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Few private houses in Brazil have an earthed supply, so even if a three-pin socket is present it is not safe to assume that all three terminals are actually connected.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Most large domestic appliances were sold with the option to fit a flying earth tail to be locally earthed, but many consumers were unsure how to use this and so did not connect it.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The new standard has an earth pin, which in theory eliminates the need for the flying earth tail.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Due to their smaller pin diameter, Brazilian plugs rated for 10 A also fit into Brazilian sockets rated for 20 A and South African sockets rated for 16 A.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] 20 A plugs do not fit into 10 A sockets, which is as intended.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] However, if the Brazilian and South African variants are mixed, due to receptacle tolerances it might be possible to insert a 16 A plug into a 10 A socket or a 20 A plug into a 16 A socket, which could overload the socket.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug defined in SI 32 (IS16A-R) is used only in Israel, the Gaza Strip and the West Bank.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There are two versions: an older one with flat pins, and a newer one with round pins.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The pre-1989 system has three flat pins in a Y-shape, with live and neutral 19 mm (0.75 in) apart.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Pre-1989 sockets which accept only old-style plugs have become very rare in Israel.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Sockets have a defined polarity; looking at the front, neutral is to the left, ground at the bottom, and live to the right.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Italian plugs and sockets are defined by the standard CEI 23-50 and referred to as "Type L".
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This includes models rated at 10 A and 16 A that differ in contact diameter and spacing.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Both are symmetrical, allowing the live and neutral contacts to be inserted in either direction.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The 10 A plug has 4 mm diameter pins and the centres spaced 19 mm apart, while the 16 A plug has 5 mm diameter pins and the centres spaced 26 mm apart.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This plug type is also used in Chile and Uruguay.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Modern installations in Italy (and in other countries where Type L plugs are used) typically use sockets that accept several plug types.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The simplest type, designated CEI 23-50 P17/11, has a central round hole flanked by two figure-8 shaped holes, allowing the insertion of Italian 10 A and 16 A plugs as well as Europlugs.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] These compact hybrid sockets are known as *presa bipasso* (twin-gauge socket).
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] A larger, but more flexible hybrid socket is called CEI 23-50 P40.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It merges the *bipasso* form factor with a "Schuko" socket, thus also accepting earthed CEE 7/4 (Schuko) and CEE 7/7 (CEE hybrid) as well as unearthed CEE 7/17 ("contour") plugs.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Many appliances sold in Italy today are equipped with hybrid CEE 7/7 or CEE 7/17 plugs, but only these larger CEI 23-50 P40 sockets will accept them without an adapter.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] However, adaptors that allow plugging them into smaller sockets are also commonly sold and regulated by a specific standard.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Ordinary duplex socket mounted in ground-pin down orientation.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Most of North America and Central America, and some of South America, use connectors standardized by the National Electrical Manufacturers Association (NEMA).
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The devices are named using the format NEMA n-mmX, where *n* is an identifier for the configuration of pins and blades, *mm* is the maximum current rating, and *X* is either P for plug or R for receptacle.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] For example, NEMA 5-15R is a configuration type 5 receptacle supporting 15 A.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Corresponding *P* and *R* versions are designed to be mated.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Within the series, the arrangement and size of pins will differ, to prevent accidental mating of devices with a higher current draw than the receptacle can support.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] NEMA-1 plugs have two parallel blades and are rated 15 A at 125 volts.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] They provide no ground connection but will fit into a grounding NEMA 5-15 receptacle.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Early versions were not polarized, but today most plugs are polarized via a wider neutral blade.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] (Unpolarized AC adaptors are a common exception.) Harvey Hubbell patented a parallel blade plug in 1913, where the blades were equal width (U.S. patent 1,064,833).
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In 1916 Hubbell received a patent for a polarized version where one blade was both longer and wider than the other (U.S. patent 1,180,648).
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In the polarized version of NEMA 1-15, introduced in the 1950s, both blades are the same length, with only the width varying.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Ungrounded NEMA-1 outlets are not permitted in new construction in the United States and Canada, but can still be found in older buildings.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The NEMA 5-15 plug has two flat parallel blades like NEMA 1-15, and a ground (earth) pin.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The ground pin is longer than the live and neutral blades, such that an inserted plug connects to ground before power.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The ground hole is officially D-shaped, although some round holes exist and many plugs have round ground pins.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Both current-carrying blades on grounding plugs may be narrow, since the ground pin enforces polarity, but outlets have a wider opening for the neutral blade to prevent ungrounded polarized plugs from being put in backwards.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This socket is recommended in IEC standard 60906-2 for 120-volt 60 Hz installations.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The National Electrical Contractors Association's installation standard (NEIS 130-2016) requires a consistent orientation for sockets installed together or nearby, but does not prescribe any specific orientation.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In practice, most sockets are mounted with the ground contact below the other contacts.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This ground-down orientation has been called the "sad socket", "dismayed face", or "shocked face" – names which reflect pareidolia.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Tamper-resistant sockets may be required in new residential construction, with shutters on the power blade sockets to prevent contact by objects inserted into the socket.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In stage lighting, this connector is sometimes known as *PBG* for *Parallel Blade with Ground*, *Edison* or *Hubbell*, the name of a common manufacturer.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The NEMA 5-20 AP variant has blades perpendicular to each other.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The receptacle has a T-slot for the neutral blade which accepts either 15 A parallel-blade plugs or 20 A plugs.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] NEMA 14-50 devices are frequently found in RV parks, since they are used for "shore power" connections of larger recreational vehicles.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Also, it was formerly common to connect mobile homes to utility power via a 14-50 device.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Newer applications include Tesla's Mobile Connector for vehicle charging, which formally recommended the installation of a 14-50 receptacle for home use.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] 240 V 20-, 30- and 50-amp rated sockets are often used for high-current appliances such as air conditioners, clothes dryers and electric stoves, respectively.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Japanese Class II plug and socket appear physically identical to NEMA 1-15 and also carries 15 A.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The relevant Japanese Industrial Standards, JIS C 8303, imposes stricter dimensional requirements for the plug housing, different marking requirements, and mandatory testing and type approval.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Older Japanese sockets and multi-plug adaptors are unpolarized—the slots in the sockets are the same size—and will accept only unpolarized plugs.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Japanese plugs generally fit into most North American sockets without modification, but polarized North American plugs may require adaptors or replacement non-polarized plugs to connect to older Japanese sockets.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Japan the voltage is 100 V, and the frequency is either 50 Hz (Eastern Japan: Tokyo, Yokohama, Tohoku, Kawasaki, Sapporo, Sendai and Hokkaido) or 60 Hz (Western Japan: Osaka, Kyoto, Nagoya, Shikoku, Kyushu and Hiroshima) depending on whether the customer is located on the Osaka or Tokyo grid.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Therefore, some North American devices which can be physically plugged into Japanese sockets may not function properly.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Japan also uses a grounded plug similar to the North American NEMA 5-15.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] However, it is less common than its NEMA 1-15 equivalent.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Since 2005, new Japanese homes are required to have class I grounded sockets for connecting domestic appliances.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This rule does not apply for sockets not intended to be used for domestic appliances, but it is strongly advised to have class I sockets throughout the home.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Swiss standard, also used in Liechtenstein, is *SN 441011* (*SN SEV 1011 until 2019) Plugs and socket-outlets for household and similar purposes*.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The standard defines a hierarchical system of plugs and sockets with two, three and five pins, and 10 A or 16 A ratings.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Sockets will accept plugs with the same or fewer pins and the same or lower ratings.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The standard does not require the use of child protective shutters.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] SN 441011 defines a "Type 1x" series of 10 A plugs and sockets.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The type 11 plug is unearthed, with two 4 mm diameter round pins spaced 19 mm apart.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The type 12 plug adds a central 4 mm diameter round earth pin, offset by 5 mm.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The obsolete type 12 socket had no recess, while the newer type 13 socket is recessed.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Both sockets will accept type 11 and type 12 plugs, and also the 2.5 A Europlug.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Earlier type 11 and 12 plugs had live and neutral pins without sleeved pins, which present a shock hazard when partially inserted into non-recessed sockets.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The IEC Type J designation refers to SEV 1011's type 12 plugs and type 13 sockets.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Unique to Switzerland is a three-phase power socket compatible with single-phase plugs: The type 15 plug has three round pins, of the same dimensions as type 12, plus two smaller flat rectangular pins for two additional power phases.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The type 15 socket is recessed, and has five openings (three round and two flat rectangular).
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It will accept plugs of types 11, 12, 15 and the Europlug.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] SN 441011 also defines a "Type 2x" series of 16 A plugs and sockets.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] These are the same as their 10 A "Type 1x" counterparts, but replace the round pins with 4 mm × 5 mm rectangular pins.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The sockets will also accept "Type 1x" plugs.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The unearthed type 21 plug has two rectangular pins, with centres 19 mm apart.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The type 23 plug adds a central rectangular earth pin, offset by 5 mm.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The recessed type 23 socket will accept plugs of types 11, 12, 21, 23 and the Europlug.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Again, the three-phase power socket is compatible with single-phase plugs, either of 10 A or 16 A ratings.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The type 25 plug has three rectangular pins of the same dimensions as type 23, plus two rectangular pins of the same dimensions as type 15.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The corresponding type 25 socket is recessed and will accept all Swiss plug types as well as the Europlug.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Thai Industrial Standard (TIS) 166-2547 and its subsequent update TIS 166-2549 replaced prior standards which were based on NEMA 1-15 and 5-15, as Thailand uses 230 V electricity.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug has two round power pins 4.8 mm in diameter and 19 mm in length, insulated for 10 mm and spaced 19 mm apart, with an earthing pin of the same diameter and 21.4 mm in length, located 11.89 mm from the line connecting the two power pins.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The earth pin spacing corresponds to that of NEMA 5 and provides compatibility with prior hybrid three-pin sockets, which accept NEMA 1-15, NEMA 5-15, and Europlugs, all of which have been variably used in Thailand.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The standard also defines an ungrounded plug with a smaller form factor that is very similar to the Europlug (but a bit higher); its power pins are identical to the grounded variant and both are rated for up to 16 A (while the Europlug is only rated for 2.5 A).
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The generally used hybrid socket is also defined in TIS 166-2547, in addition to a plain three-round-pin socket, with plans to eventually replace the former and phase out support for NEMA-compatible plugs.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Sockets are polarized (as in NEMA 5-15).
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The grounded plug is similar to, but not interchangeable with, the Israeli SI32 plug.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Thai plug is designated as "Type O" at IEC World Plugs.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Special purpose sockets may be found in residential, industrial, commercial or institutional buildings.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Special-purpose sockets may be labelled or coloured to identify a reserved use of a system, or may have keys or specially shaped pins to prevent use of unintended equipment.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plugs and sockets used to power electric stoves from a single-phase line have to be rated for greater current values than those used with three-phase supply because all the power has to be transferred through two contacts, not three.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] If not hardwired to the supply, electric stoves may be connected to the mains with an appropriate high power connector.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Some countries do not have wiring regulations for single-phase electric stoves.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Russia, an electric stove can often be seen connected with a 25, 32, or even 40 A connector.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Norway, a 25 A grounded connector, rectangular shaped with rounded corners, is used for single-phase stoves.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The connector has three rectangular pins in a row, with the grounding pin longer than other two.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The corresponding socket is recessed to prevent shocks.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Norwegian standard is NEK 502:2005 – standard sheet X (socket) and sheet XI (plug).
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] National wiring regulations sometimes prohibit the use of sockets adjacent to water taps, etc.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] A special socket, with an isolation transformer, may allow electric razors to be used near a sink.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Because the isolation transformer is of low rating, such outlets are not suitable to operate higher-powered appliances such as hair dryers.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] An IEC standard 61558-2-5, adopted by CENELEC and as a national standard in some countries, describes one type of shaver supply unit.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Shaver sockets may accept multiple two-pin plug types including Australian (Type I) and BS 4573.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The isolation transformer often includes a 115 V output accepting two-pin US plugs (Type A).
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Shaver supply units must also be current limited, IEC 61558-2-5 specifies a minimum rating of 20 VA and maximum of 50 VA.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Sockets are marked with a shaver symbol, and may also say "shavers only".
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Isolation transformers and dedicated NEMA 1-15 shaver receptacles were once standard installation practice in North America, but now a GFCI receptacle is used instead.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This provides the full capacity of a standard receptacle but protects the user of a razor or other appliance from leakage current.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Though BS 4573 plugs look similar to Europlugs (Type C), there are subtle differences between them.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] While the BS 4573 plug has round 5 mm contacts, spaced at 16 mm, the Europlug has 4 mm contacts, spaced at (roughly) 19 mm.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In order to insert a Europlug into a BS 4573 socket, an adaptor should be used.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Polarized plugs have a wider neutral blade; sockets accept both polarized and unpolarized plugs.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CEE 7/17 specifies an unearthed hybrid plug that fits into both the CEE 7/3 and CEE 7/5 sockets.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There are some CEE 7/17 plugs with special shape which are polarized when used with CEE 7/5 sockets (mechanically only).
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The recess provided by CEE 7/3 and CEE 7/5 sockets offers protection against touching the live pins of CEE 7/4, CEE 7/6, CEE 7/7, and CEE 7/17 plugs.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] When used in CEE 7/1 (unearthed) sockets or "universal adaptors" there is no protection for those plugs.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CEE 7/1 socket accepts earthed CEE 7/3, CEE 7/5 and CEE 7/7 plugs but provides no earth connection.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Older sockets can have a very shallow recess.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] BS 4573 and BS EN 61558-2-5 do not explicitly specify a current rating for a compliant plug, see BS 4573 section of British and compatible standards.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CEE 7/7 specifies an earthed hybrid plug that fits into both the CEE 7/3 and CEE 7/5 sockets.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Plug can only be inserted one way with French CEE 7/5, but lack of wiring convention means that the system is not polarized.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The actual rating of non-rewirable plugs is marked according to the fuse fitted by the cord set manufacturer, the fuse rating being determined by the rating of the flexible cable.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Also accepts unearthed Class II plugs that include an unwired dummy earth pin.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Except when used with unearthed plugs such as the Europlug.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Sockets may be recessed by 8.3 mm, but few are.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There are unearthed Class II plugs with an unwired dummy earth pin, accepted by all sockets.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There are also unearthed Class II plugs without an earth pin, accepted only by sockets that do not have an earth-pin-driven shutter.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Import of plugs with non-partially-insulated pins no longer allowed after 2012.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Unrecessed type 12 sockets may no longer be installed since 2017.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The recess provided by some Danish sockets offers protection against touching the live pins of plugs.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Sockets must be recessed or equipped with a switch that allows them to be turned off.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Type L comes in two variations with ratings of 10 A and 16 A having different pin diameters and spacing from each other.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Also used in Paraguay (PNA-IEC 60906-1).
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Italian bypass lampholder plugs with Edison screw mount.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] A lampholder plug fits into a light socket in place of a light bulb to connect appliances to lighting circuits.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Where a lower rate was applied to electric power used for lighting circuits, lampholder plugs enabled the consumers to reduce their electricity costs.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Edison screw lampholder adaptors (for NEMA 1-15 plugs) are still commonly used in the Americas.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] This Soviet plug, now rarely used, has pin dimensions and spacing equal to the Europlug, but lacks the insulation sleeves.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] It has a round body like the European CEE 7/2 or flat body with a round base like CEE 7/17.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The pins are parallel and do not converge.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The body is made of fire-resistant thermoset plastic.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The corresponding 6 A socket accepts the Europlug, but not others as the 4.5 mm holes are too small to accept the 4.8 mm pins of CEE 7/4, CEE 7/6 or CEE 7/7 plugs.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] There were also moulded rubber plugs available for devices up to 16 A similar to CEE 7/17, but with a round base without any notches.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] They could be altered to fit a CEE 7/5 or CEE 7/3 socket by cutting notches with a sharp knife.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Some appliances sold in the Soviet Union had a flat unearthed plug with an additional pass-through socket on the top, allowing a stacked arrangement of plugs.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The pins of the secondary plug (which lacked insulation sleeves) could not be inserted into the cylindrical sockets completely, leaving a 5 mm gap between the primary and secondary plugs.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The adaptors were mostly used for low power appliances (for example, connecting both a table lamp and a radio to a socket).
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Compared to the standard BS 1363 plugs found in the UK, each pin is rotated 90 degrees.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] This style of plug/socket was used by university laboratories (from batteries) and the BBC, and is still in use in parts of the London Underground for 110 V AC voltage supply.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] In the 1960s they were used for 240 V DC in the Power laboratory of the Electrical Engineering department of what was then University College, Cardiff.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Power was supplied by the public 240 V DC mains which remained available in addition to the 240 V AC mains until circa 1969, and thereafter from in-house rectifiers.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] They were also used in the Ministry of Defence Main Building inside circuits powered from the standby generators to stop staff from plugging in unauthorized devices.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] They were also known to be used in some British Rail offices for the same reason.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] In the 1960s, Italian firm BTicino introduced an alternative to the Europlug or CEI 23-16 connectors then in use, called Magic Security.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The socket is rectangular with lateral key pins and indentations to maintain polarization and prevent insertion of a plug with different current ratings.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Three single-phase general purpose connectors were rated 10 A, 16 A and 20 A; and a three-phase industrial connector rated 10 A; all of them have different key-pin positioning so plugs and sockets cannot be mismatched.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The socket is closed by a safety lid (bearing the word *Magic* on it) which can be opened only with an even pressure on its surface, thus preventing the insertion of objects (except the plug itself) inside the socket.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The contacts are positioned on both sides of the plug; the plug is energised only when it is inserted fully into the socket.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The system is not compatible with Italian CEI plugs, nor with Europlugs.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Appliances were never sold fitted with these security plugs, and the use of adaptors would defeat the safety features, so the supplied plugs had to be cut off and replaced with the security connector.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Even so, the *Magic* security system had some success at first because its enhanced safety features appealed to customers; standard connectors of the day were not considered safe enough.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The decline of the system occurred when safety lids similar to the Magic type were developed for standard sockets.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] In Italy, the system was never definitively abandoned.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Though very rarely seen today, it is still marked as available in BTicino's catalogue, (except for the three-phase version, which stopped being produced in July 2011).
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] In Chile, 10 A Magic connectors are commonly used for computer/laboratory power networks, as well as for communications or data equipment.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] This allows delicate electronics equipment to be connected to an independent circuit breaker, usually including a surge protector or an uninterruptible power supply backup.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The different style of plug makes it more difficult for office workers to connect computer equipment to a standard unprotected power line, or to overload the UPS by connecting other office appliances.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] In Iceland, Magic plugs were widely used in homes and businesses alongside Europlug and Schuko installations.
[src:electronic-component/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Their installation in new homes was still quite common even in the late 1980s.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] An **accelerometer** is a device that measures the proper acceleration of an object.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] Proper acceleration is the acceleration (the rate of change of velocity) of the object relative to an observer who is in free fall (that is, relative to an inertial frame of reference).
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] Proper acceleration is different from coordinate acceleration, which is acceleration with respect to a given coordinate system, which may or may not be accelerating.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] For example, an accelerometer at rest on the surface of the Earth will measure an acceleration due to Earth's gravity straight upwards of about *g* ≈ 9.81 m/s2.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] By contrast, an accelerometer that is in free fall will measure zero acceleration.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] Highly sensitive accelerometers are used in inertial navigation systems for aircraft and missiles.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] In unmanned aerial vehicles, accelerometers help to stabilize flight.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] Micromachined micro-electromechanical systems (MEMS) accelerometers are used in handheld electronic devices such as smartphones, cameras and video-game controllers to detect movement and orientation of these devices.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] Vibration in industrial machinery is monitored by accelerometers.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] Seismometers are sensitive accelerometers for monitoring ground movement such as earthquakes.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] When two or more accelerometers are coordinated with one another, they can measure differences in proper acceleration, particularly gravity, over their separation in space—that is, the gradient of the gravitational field.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] Gravity gradiometry is useful because absolute gravity is a weak effect and depends on the local density of the Earth, which is quite variable.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] A single-axis accelerometer measures acceleration along a specified axis.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] A multi-axis accelerometer detects both the magnitude and the direction of the proper acceleration, as a vector quantity, and is usually implemented as several single-axis accelerometers oriented along different axes.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] An accelerometer measures proper acceleration, which is the acceleration it experiences relative to freefall and is the acceleration felt by people and objects.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] Put another way, at any point in spacetime the equivalence principle guarantees the existence of a local inertial frame, and an accelerometer measures the acceleration relative to that frame.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] Such accelerations are popularly denoted g-force; i.e., in comparison to standard gravity.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] An accelerometer at rest relative to the Earth's surface will indicate approximately 1 g *upwards* because the Earth's surface exerts a normal force upwards relative to the local inertial frame (the frame of a freely falling object near the surface).
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] To obtain the acceleration due to motion with respect to the Earth, this "gravity offset" must be subtracted and corrections made for effects caused by the Earth's rotation relative to the inertial frame.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] The reason for the appearance of a gravitational offset is Einstein's equivalence principle, which states that the effects of gravity on an object are indistinguishable from acceleration.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] When held fixed in a gravitational field by, for example, applying a ground reaction force or an equivalent upward thrust, the reference frame for an accelerometer (its own casing) accelerates upwards with respect to a free-falling reference frame.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] For similar reasons, an accelerometer will read *zero* during any type of free fall.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] This includes use in a coasting spaceship in deep space far from any mass, a spaceship orbiting the Earth, an airplane in a parabolic "zero-g" arc, or any free-fall in a vacuum.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] Another example is free-fall at a sufficiently high altitude that atmospheric effects can be neglected.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] However, this does not include a (non-free) fall in which air resistance produces drag forces that reduce the acceleration until constant terminal velocity is reached.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] At terminal velocity, the accelerometer will indicate 1 g acceleration upwards.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] For the same reason a skydiver, upon reaching terminal velocity, does not feel as though he or she were in "free-fall", but rather experiences a feeling similar to being supported (at 1 g) on a "bed" of uprushing air.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] Acceleration is quantified in the SI unit metres per second per second (m/s2), in the cgs unit gal (Gal), or popularly in terms of standard gravity (*g*).
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] For the practical purpose of finding the acceleration of objects with respect to the Earth, such as for use in an inertial navigation system, a knowledge of local gravity is required.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] This can be obtained either by calibrating the device at rest, or from a known model of gravity at the approximate current position.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] A basic mechanical accelerometer is a damped proof mass on a spring.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] When the accelerometer experiences an acceleration, Newton's third law causes the spring's compression (or extension) to adjust to exert an equivalent force on the mass to counteract the acceleration.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] Since the spring's force scales linearly with the length change (according to Hooke's law) and because the spring constant and mass are known constants, a measurement of the spring's compression (or extension) is also a measurement of acceleration.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] The system is damped to prevent oscillations of the mass and spring interfering with measurements.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] However, the damping causes accelerometers to have a frequency response.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] Many animals have sensory organs to detect acceleration, especially gravity.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] In these, the proof mass is usually one or more crystals of calcium carbonate otoliths (Latin for "ear stone") or statoconia, acting against a bed of hairs connected to neurons.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] The hairs form the springs, with the neurons as sensors.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] Many vertebrates, including humans, have these structures in their inner ears.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] Most invertebrates have similar organs, but not as part of their hearing organs.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] Mechanical accelerometers are often designed so that an electronic circuit senses a small amount of motion, then pushes on the proof mass with some type of linear motor to keep the proof mass from moving far.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] The motor might be an electromagnet or in very small accelerometers, electrostatic.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] Since the circuit's electronic behavior can be carefully designed, and the proof mass does not move far, these designs can be very stable (i.e. they do not oscillate), very linear with a controlled frequency response.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] In mechanical accelerometers, measurement is often electrical, piezoelectric, piezoresistive or capacitive.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] Piezoelectric accelerometers use piezoceramic sensors (e.g. lead zirconate titanate) or single crystals (e.g. quartz, tourmaline).
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] They are unmatched in high frequency measurements, low packaged weight, and resistance to high temperatures.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] Piezoresistive accelerometers resist shock (very high accelerations) better.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] Capacitive accelerometers typically use a silicon micro-machined sensing element.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] Modern mechanical accelerometers are often small *micro-electro-mechanical systems* (MEMS), and are often very simple MEMS devices, consisting of little more than a cantilever beam with a proof mass (also known as *seismic mass*).
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] Damping results from the residual gas sealed in the device.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] As long as the Q-factor is not too low, damping does not result in a lower sensitivity.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] Under the influence of external accelerations, the proof mass deflects from its neutral position.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] This deflection is measured in an analog or digital manner.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] Most commonly, the capacitance between a set of fixed beams and a set of beams attached to the proof mass is measured.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] This method is simple, reliable, and inexpensive.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] Integrating piezoresistors in the springs to detect spring deformation, and thus deflection, is a good alternative, although a few more process steps are needed during the fabrication sequence.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] For very high sensitivities quantum tunnelling is also used; this requires a dedicated process making it very expensive.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] Optical measurement has been demonstrated in laboratory devices.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] Another MEMS-based accelerometer is a thermal (or convective) accelerometer.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] It contains a small heater in a very small dome.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] This heats the air or other fluid inside the dome.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] The thermal bubble acts as the proof mass.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] An accompanying temperature sensor (like a thermistor; or thermopile) in the dome measures the temperature in one location of the dome.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] This measures the location of the heated bubble within the dome.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] When the dome is accelerated, the colder, higher density fluid pushes the heated bubble.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] The temperature measurement is interpreted as acceleration.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] Gravity acting on the fluid provides the spring.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] Since the proof mass is very lightweight gas, and not held by a beam or lever, thermal accelerometers can survive high shocks.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] Another variation uses a wire to both heat the gas and detect the change in temperature.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] The change of temperature changes the resistance of the wire.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] A two dimensional accelerometer can be economically constructed with one dome, one bubble and two measurement devices.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] Most micromechanical accelerometers operate *in-plane*, that is, they are designed to be sensitive only to a direction in the plane of the die.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] By integrating two devices perpendicularly on a single die a two-axis accelerometer can be made.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] By adding another *out-of-plane* device, three axes can be measured.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] Such a combination may have much lower misalignment error than three discrete models combined after packaging.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] Micromechanical accelerometers are available in a wide variety of measuring ranges, reaching up to thousands of *g*'s.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] The designer must compromise between sensitivity and the maximum acceleration that can be measured.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] Accelerometers can be used to measure vehicle acceleration.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] Accelerometers can be used to measure vibration on cars, machines, buildings, process control systems and safety installations.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] They can also be used to measure seismic activity, inclination, machine vibration, dynamic distance and speed with or without the influence of gravity.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] Applications for accelerometers that measure gravity, wherein an accelerometer is specifically configured for use in gravimetry, are called gravimeters.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] Accelerometers are also increasingly used in the biological sciences.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] High frequency recordings of bi-axial or tri-axial acceleration allows the discrimination of behavioral patterns while animals are out of sight.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] For example, accelerometers have been used to study flight energy expenditure of Harris's Hawk (*Parabuteo unicinctus*).
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] Researchers are also using smartphone accelerometers to collect and extract mechano-biological descriptors of resistance exercise.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] Increasingly, researchers are deploying accelerometers with additional technology, such as cameras or microphones, to better understand animal behaviour in the wild (for example, hunting behaviour of Canada lynx).
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] Accelerometers are also used for machinery health monitoring to report the vibration and its changes in time of shafts at the bearings of rotating equipment such as turbines, pumps, fans, rollers, compressors, or bearing fault which, if not attended to promptly, can lead to costly repairs.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] Accelerometer vibration data allows the user to monitor machines and detect these faults before the rotating equipment fails completely.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] Accelerometers are widely used in structural health monitoring (SHM) of buildings, bridges and other civil infrastructure to record the dynamic response under ambient and forced loads (e.g., wind, traffic, machinery and earthquakes).
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] From these vibration records, engineers estimate modal properties—natural frequencies, damping ratios and mode shapes—often using operational modal analysis (OMA) techniques for in-service structures.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] These parameters are trended over time for condition assessment and model updating.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] In seismic regions, arrays of accelerometers installed in buildings and other structures provide strong-motion data for rapid post-event assessments and long-term performance studies.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] Geological Survey's National Strong-Motion Project (NSMP) operates structural arrays and distributes building and structural records via the Center for Engineering Strong Motion Data (CESMD).
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] Instrumentation and data-quality practices for building vibration measurements are guided by international standards.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] ISO 4866 provides principles for measuring the vibration of fixed structures and evaluating vibration effects based on structural response, while ISO 10137 gives serviceability recommendations for buildings and walkways with respect to human perception, contents and the structure itself.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] Choice of accelerometer technology depends on frequency range and amplitude.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] Piezoelectric accelerometers are common for higher-frequency, higher-amplitude measurements, whereas low-noise MEMS accelerometers have become attractive for low-frequency building and bridge monitoring and for dense or wireless deployments due to cost and power advantages.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] Recent evaluations and developments show that appropriately selected MEMS devices can identify modal parameters with acceptable accuracy for SHM and have been integrated into high-sensitivity wireless nodes.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] Networked and wireless smart-sensor approaches allow distributed monitoring at scale.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] Reviews document the shift from wired to wireless SHM systems and the maturation of wireless smart-sensor networks for tasks such as ambient-vibration modal identification and continuous trending.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] Accelerometers are often fused with other sensors to improve displacement and drift estimation, especially for large or flexible structures.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] GNSS provides quasi-static and very-low-frequency motion that complements accelerometer-based dynamics; recent studies report accurate dynamic displacement retrieval using high-rate or multi-GNSS solutions combined with accelerometers.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] Beyond permanently instrumented assets, indirect and crowdsourced approaches using smartphone accelerometers have been explored, particularly for bridges.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] Research has shown that modal frequencies—and in some cases spatial vibration characteristics—can be estimated from accelerometer data collected by vehicles crossing bridges, offering a complementary, low-cost screening tool for large inventories.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] Related work has also evaluated smartphone-based ambient vibration monitoring of buildings.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] Long-term case studies illustrate large-scale deployments.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] Hong Kong's Wind and Structural Health Monitoring System (WASHMS) has instrumented the Tsing Ma Bridge since 1997; subsequent publications report decades of monitoring for load and response in service.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] Scotland's Queensferry Crossing was equipped with a comprehensive SHM system including thousands of sensors, and Sydney Harbour Bridge has been reported as instrumented with thousands of sensors for real-time monitoring.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] SHM data are used for continuous condition tracking, event-triggered assessments (e.g., after earthquakes), and to support asset management decisions.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] In bridge engineering, guidance from transportation agencies describes how field data—including accelerometer measurements—can be integrated with inspection and nondestructive evaluation to improve load-rating reliability and maintenance planning.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] Zoll's AED Plus uses CPR-D•padz which contain an accelerometer to measure the depth of CPR chest compressions.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] Within the last several years, several companies have produced and marketed sports watches for runners that include footpods, containing accelerometers to help determine the speed and distance for the runner wearing the unit.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] In Belgium, accelerometer-based step counters are promoted by the government to encourage people to walk a few thousand steps each day.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] Herman Digital Trainer uses accelerometers to measure strike force in physical training.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] It has been suggested to build football helmets with accelerometers in order to measure the impact of head collisions.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] The US Army Research Laboratory developed the Three-Axis Acceleration Switch which has been suggested for this application.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] Accelerometers have been used to calculate gait parameters, such as stance and swing phase.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] This kind of sensor can be used to measure or monitor people.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] An inertial navigation system is a navigation aid that uses a computer and motion sensors (accelerometers) to continuously calculate via dead reckoning the position, orientation, and velocity (direction and speed of movement) of a moving object without the need for external references.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] Other terms used to refer to inertial navigation systems or closely related devices include inertial guidance system, inertial reference platform, and many other variations.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] An accelerometer alone is unsuitable to determine changes in altitude over distances where the vertical decrease of gravity is significant, such as for aircraft and rockets.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] In the presence of a gravitational gradient, the calibration and data reduction process is numerically unstable.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] Accelerometers are used to detect apogee in both professional and in amateur rocketry.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] Accelerometers are also being used in Intelligent Compaction rollers.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] Accelerometers are used alongside gyroscopes in inertial navigation systems.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] One of the most common uses for MEMS accelerometers is in airbag deployment systems for modern automobiles.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] In this case, the accelerometers are used to detect the rapid negative acceleration of the vehicle to determine when a collision has occurred and the severity of the collision.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] Another common automotive use is in electronic stability control systems, which use a lateral accelerometer to measure cornering forces.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] The widespread use of accelerometers in the automotive industry has pushed their cost down dramatically.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] Another automotive application is the monitoring of noise, vibration, and harshness (NVH), conditions that cause discomfort for drivers and passengers and may also be indicators of mechanical faults.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] Tilting trains use accelerometers and gyroscopes to calculate the required tilt.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] Modern electronic accelerometers are used in remote sensing devices intended for the monitoring of active volcanoes to detect the motion of magma.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] Accelerometers are increasingly being incorporated into personal electronic devices to detect the orientation of the device, for example, a display screen.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] A *free-fall sensor* (FFS) is an accelerometer used to detect if a system has been dropped and is falling.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] It can then apply safety measures such as parking the head of a hard disk to prevent a head crash and resulting data loss upon impact.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] This device is included in the many common computer and consumer electronic products that are produced by a variety of manufacturers.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] It is also used in some data loggers to monitor handling operations for shipping containers.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] The length of time in free fall is used to calculate the height of drop and to estimate the shock to the package.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] Some smartphones, digital audio players and personal digital assistants contain accelerometers for user interface control; often the accelerometer is used to present landscape or portrait views of the device's screen, based on the way the device is being held.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] Apple has included an accelerometer in every generation of iPhone, iPad, and iPod touch, as well as in every iPod nano since the 4th generation.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] Along with orientation view adjustment, accelerometers in mobile devices can also be used as pedometers, in conjunction with specialized applications.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] Automatic Collision Notification (ACN) systems also use accelerometers in a system to call for help in event of a vehicle crash.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] Prominent ACN systems include OnStar AACN service, Ford Link's 911 Assist, Toyota's Safety Connect, Lexus Link, or BMW Assist.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] Many accelerometer-equipped smartphones also have ACN software available for download.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] ACN systems are activated by detecting crash-strength accelerations.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] Accelerometers are used in vehicle Electronic stability control systems to measure the vehicle's actual movement.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] A computer compares the vehicle's actual movement to the driver's steering and throttle input.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] The stability control computer can selectively brake individual wheels and/or reduce engine power to minimize the difference between driver input and the vehicle's actual movement.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] This can help prevent the vehicle from spinning or rolling over.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] Some pedometers use an accelerometer to more accurately measure the number of steps taken and distance traveled than a mechanical sensor can provide.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] Nintendo's Wii video game console uses a controller called a Wii Remote that contains a three-axis accelerometer and was designed primarily for motion input.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] Users also have the option of buying an additional motion-sensitive attachment, the Nunchuk, so that motion input could be recorded from both of the user's hands independently.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] Is also used on the Nintendo 3DS system.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] Sleep phase alarm clocks use accelerometric sensors to detect movement of a sleeper, so that it can wake the person when he/she is not in REM phase, in order to awaken the person more easily.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] A microphone or eardrum is a membrane that responds to oscillations in air pressure.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] These oscillations cause acceleration, so accelerometers can be used to record sound.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] A 2012 study found that voices can be detected in 93% of typical daily situations by accelerometers like those in smartphones fixed to the sternum.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] Conversely, carefully designed sounds can cause accelerometers to report false data.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] One study tested 20 models of (MEMS) smartphone accelerometers and found that a majority were susceptible to this attack.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] A number of 21st-century devices use accelerometers to align the screen depending on the direction the device is held (e.g., switching between portrait and landscape modes).
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] Such devices include many tablet PCs and some smartphones and digital cameras.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] The Amida Simputer, a handheld Linux device launched in 2004, was the first commercial handheld to have a built-in accelerometer.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] It incorporated many gesture-based interactions using this accelerometer, including page-turning, zoom-in and zoom-out of images, change of portrait to landscape mode, and many simple gesture-based games.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] As of January 2009, almost all new mobile phones and digital cameras contain at least a tilt sensor and sometimes an accelerometer for the purpose of auto image rotation, motion-sensitive mini-games, and correcting shake when taking photographs.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] Camcorders use accelerometers for image stabilization, either by moving optical elements to adjust the light path to the sensor to cancel out unintended motions or digitally shifting the image to smooth out detected motion.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] Some stills cameras use accelerometers for anti-blur capturing.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] The camera holds off capturing the image when the camera is moving.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] When the camera is still (if only for a millisecond, as could be the case for vibration), the image is captured.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] An example of the application of this technology is the Glogger VS2, a phone application which runs on Symbian based phones with accelerometers such as the Nokia N96.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] Some digital cameras contain accelerometers to determine the orientation of the photo being taken and also for rotating the current picture when viewing.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] Many laptops feature an accelerometer which is used to detect drops.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] If a drop is detected, the heads of the hard disk are parked to avoid data loss and possible head or disk damage by the ensuing shock.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] A gravimeter, or gravitometer, is an instrument used in gravimetry for measuring the local gravitational field.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] A gravimeter is a type of accelerometer, except that accelerometers are susceptible to all vibrations including noise, that cause oscillatory accelerations.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] This is counteracted in the gravimeter by integral vibration isolation and signal processing.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] Though the essential principle of design is the same as in accelerometers, gravimeters are typically designed to be much more sensitive than accelerometers in order to measure very tiny changes within the Earth's gravity, of 1 *g*.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] In contrast, other accelerometers are often designed to measure 1000 *g* or more, and many perform multi-axial measurements.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] The constraints on temporal resolution are usually less for gravimeters, so that resolution can be increased by processing the output with a longer "time constant".
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] If done without a user's knowledge or consent, this is referred to as an inference attack.
[src:electronic-component/accelerometer] Additionally, millions of smartphones could be vulnerable to software cracking via accelerometers.
[src:electronic-component/acorn-tube] An **acorn tube**, or **acorn valve**, is any member of a family of VHF/UHF vacuum tubes starting just before World War II.
[src:electronic-component/acorn-tube] They were named after their resemblance to the acorn, specifically due to the glass cap at one end of the tube that looked similar to the cap on an acorn.
[src:electronic-component/acorn-tube] The acorn tubes found widespread use in radios and radar systems.
[src:electronic-component/acorn-tube] High-frequency performance is limited by (1) parasitic lead inductance and capacitance and skin effect, and (2) electron transit time (the time required to travel from cathode to anode).
[src:electronic-component/acorn-tube] Transit time effects are complicated, but one simple effect is the phase margin; another one is input conductance, also known as grid loading.
[src:electronic-component/acorn-tube] At extremely high frequencies, electrons arriving at the grid may become out of phase with those departing towards the anode.
[src:electronic-component/acorn-tube] This imbalance of charge causes the grid to exhibit a reactance that is much less than its low-frequency "open circuit" characteristic.
[src:electronic-component/acorn-tube] Acorn- as well as Lighthouse tubes and Nuvistors attempt to minimize this effect by arranging cathode, grid(s) and anode as closely spaced together as possible.
[src:electronic-component/acorn-tube] The original range included about half a dozen tubes, designed to work in the VHF range.
[src:electronic-component/acorn-tube] The 954 and 956 types are sharp and remote cut-off pentodes, respectively, all with indirect 6.3 V, 150 mA heaters.
[src:electronic-component/acorn-tube] Types 957, 958 and 959 are for portable equipment and have 1.25 V NiCd battery heaters.
[src:electronic-component/acorn-tube] The 957 is a medium-μ signal triode, the 958 is a transmitting triode with dual, paralleled filaments for increased emission, and the 959 is a sharp cut-off pentode like the 954.
[src:electronic-component/acorn-tube] The 957 and 959 draw 50 mA heater current, the 958 twice as much.
[src:electronic-component/acorn-tube] In 1942, the 958A with tightened emission specifications was introduced after it turned out that 958s with excessively high emission kept working after the filament power was turned off, the filament still sufficiently heating on the anode current alone.
[src:electronic-component/acorn-tube] After the introduction of the miniature 7-pin base, the 954, 955 and 956 were made available with this base as 9001, 9002 and 9003.
[src:electronic-component/acorn-tube] Larger, higher-power types such as the 316A, 368A, 388A, and 703A triodes and the 713A and 717A pentodes were referred to as *Doorknob* tubes.
[src:electronic-component/acorn-tube] The introduction of the EF50 was the first serious competition for the acorn design, and replaced the acorns in many roles, especially post-war when millions of surplus EF50s were dumped on the market.
[src:electronic-component/additron-tube] The **Additron** was an electron tube designed by Dr.
[src:electronic-component/additron-tube] Josef Kates, circa 1950, to replace the several individual electron tubes and support components required to perform the function of a single bit digital full adder.
[src:electronic-component/additron-tube] The Additron neither went into production at the Canadian Rogers Vacuum Tube Company, where the prototypes were built, nor was it used in the UTEC machine.
[src:electronic-component/additron-tube] It did make a widely publicized appearance at the 1950 Canadian National Exhibition operating an electronic game of Tic-Tac-Toe, dubbed *Bertie the Brain*, to show the marvels of electronic computing.
[src:electronic-component/additron-tube] The tube was registered with the Radio Television Manufacturing Association on 20 March 1951 as type 6047.
[src:electronic-component/alloy-junction-transistor] The germanium **alloy-junction transistor**, or **alloy transistor**, was an early type of bipolar junction transistor, developed at General Electric and RCA in 1951 as an improvement over the earlier grown-junction transistor.
[src:electronic-component/alloy-junction-transistor] The usual construction of an alloy-junction transistor is a germanium crystal forming the base, with emitter and collector alloy beads fused on opposite sides.
[src:electronic-component/alloy-junction-transistor] Indium and antimony were commonly used to form the alloy junctions on a bar of N-type germanium.
[src:electronic-component/alloy-junction-transistor] The collector junction pellet would be about 50 mils (thousandths of an inch) in diameter, and the emitter pellet about 20 mils.
[src:electronic-component/alloy-junction-transistor] The base region would be on the order of 1 mil (0.001 inches, 25 μm) thick.
[src:electronic-component/alloy-junction-transistor] There were several types of improved alloy-junction transistors developed over the years that they were manufactured.
[src:electronic-component/alloy-junction-transistor] All types of alloy-junction transistors became obsolete in the early 1960s, with the introduction of the planar transistor which could be mass-produced easily while alloy-junction transistors had to be made individually.
[src:electronic-component/alloy-junction-transistor] The first germanium planar transistors had much worse characteristics than alloy-junction germanium transistors of the period, but they cost much less, and the characteristics of planar transistors improved very rapidly, quickly exceeding those of all earlier germanium transistors.
[src:electronic-component/alloy-junction-transistor] The **micro-alloy transistor** (**MAT**) was developed by Philco as an improved type of alloy-junction transistor, it offered much higher speed.
[src:electronic-component/alloy-junction-transistor] It is constructed of a semiconductor crystal forming the base, into which a pair of wells are etched (similar to Philco's earlier surface-barrier transistor) on opposite sides then fusing emitter and collector alloy beads into the wells.
[src:electronic-component/alloy-junction-transistor] The **micro-alloy diffused transistor** (**MADT**), or **micro-alloy diffused-base transistor**, was developed by Philco as an improved type of micro-alloy transistor; it offered even higher speed.
[src:electronic-component/alloy-junction-transistor] It is a type of diffused-base transistor.
[src:electronic-component/alloy-junction-transistor] Before using electrochemical techniques and etching depression wells into the base semiconductor crystal material, a heated diffused phosphorus gaseous layer is created over the entire intrinsic semiconductor base crystal, creating a N-type graded base semiconductor material.
[src:electronic-component/alloy-junction-transistor] The emitter well is etched very shallow into this diffused base layer.
[src:electronic-component/alloy-junction-transistor] For high-speed operation, the collector well is etched all the way through the diffused base layer and through most of the intrinsic base semiconductor region, forming an extremely thin base region.
[src:electronic-component/alloy-junction-transistor] A doping-engineered electric field was created in the diffused base layer to reduce the charge carrier base transit time (similar to the drift-field transistor).
[src:electronic-component/alloy-junction-transistor] The **post-alloy diffused transistor** (**PADT**), or **post-alloy diffused-base transistor**, was developed by Philips (but GE and RCA filed for patent and Jacques Pankove of RCA received patent for it) as an improvement to the germanium alloy-junction transistor, it offered even higher speed.
[src:electronic-component/alloy-junction-transistor] The Philco micro-alloy diffused transistor had a mechanical weakness that ultimately limited their speed; the thin diffused base layer would break if made too thin, but to get high speed it needed to be as thin as possible.
[src:electronic-component/alloy-junction-transistor] Also it was very hard to control alloying on both sides of such a thin layer.
[src:electronic-component/alloy-junction-transistor] The post-alloy diffused transistor solved this problem by making the bulk semiconductor crystal the collector (instead of the base), which could be as thick as necessary for mechanical strength.
[src:electronic-component/alloy-junction-transistor] The diffused base layer was created on top of this.
[src:electronic-component/alloy-junction-transistor] Then two alloy beads, one P-type and one N-type were fused on top of the diffused base layer.
[src:electronic-component/alloy-junction-transistor] The bead having the same type as the base dopant then became part of the base and the bead having the opposite type from the base dopant became the emitter.
[src:electronic-component/electronic-component] An **electronic component** is any basic discrete electronic device or physical entity part of an electronic system used to affect electrons or their associated fields.
[src:electronic-component/electronic-component] Electronic components are mostly industrial products, available in a singular form and are not to be confused with electrical elements, which are conceptual abstractions representing idealized electronic components and elements.
[src:electronic-component/electronic-component] A datasheet for an electronic component is a technical document that provides detailed information about the component's specifications, characteristics, and performance.
[src:electronic-component/electronic-component] Discrete circuits are made of individual electronic components that only perform one function each as packaged, which are known as discrete components, although strictly the term discrete component refers to such a component with semiconductor material such as individual transistors.
[src:electronic-component/electronic-component] Electronic components have a number of electrical terminals or leads.
[src:electronic-component/electronic-component] These leads connect to other electrical components, often over wire, to create an electronic circuit with a particular function (for example an amplifier, radio receiver, or oscillator).
[src:electronic-component/electronic-component] Basic electronic components may be packaged discretely, as arrays or networks of like components, or integrated inside of packages such as semiconductor integrated circuits, hybrid integrated circuits, or thick film devices.
[src:electronic-component/electronic-component] The following list of electronic components focuses on the discrete version of these components, treating such packages as components in their own right.
[src:electronic-component/electronic-component] Components can be classified as passive, active, or electromechanical.
[src:electronic-component/electronic-component] The strict physics definition treats passive components as ones that cannot supply energy themselves, whereas a battery would be seen as an active component since it truly acts as a source of energy.
[src:electronic-component/electronic-component] However, electronic engineers who perform circuit analysis use a more restrictive definition of passivity.
[src:electronic-component/electronic-component] Then, the analysis only concerns the AC circuit, an abstraction that ignores DC voltages and currents (and the power associated with them) present in the real-life circuit.
[src:electronic-component/electronic-component] This fiction, for instance, lets us view an oscillator as "producing energy" even though in reality the oscillator consumes even more energy from a DC power supply, which we have chosen to ignore.
[src:electronic-component/electronic-component] Most passive components with more than two terminals can be described in terms of two-port parameters that satisfy the principle of reciprocity—though there are rare exceptions.
[src:electronic-component/electronic-component] In contrast, active components (with more than two terminals) generally lack that property.
[src:electronic-component/electronic-component] Transistors were considered the invention of the twentieth century that changed electronic circuits forever.
[src:electronic-component/electronic-component] A transistor is a semiconductor device used to amplify and switch electronic signals and electrical power.
[src:electronic-component/electronic-component] Conduct electricity easily in one direction, among more specific behaviors.
[src:electronic-component/electronic-component] Integrated Circuits can serve a variety of purposes, including acting as a timer, performing digital to analog conversion, performing amplification, or being used for logical operations.
[src:electronic-component/electronic-component] A vacuum tube is based on current conduction through a vacuum (see Vacuum tube).
[src:electronic-component/electronic-component] Components incapable of controlling current by means of another electrical signal are called *passive* devices.
[src:electronic-component/electronic-component] Resistors, capacitors, inductors, and transformers are all considered passive devices.
[src:electronic-component/electronic-component] Pass current in proportion to voltage (Ohm's law) and oppose current.
[src:electronic-component/electronic-component] Capacitors store and release electrical charge.
[src:electronic-component/electronic-component] They are used for filtering power supply lines, tuning resonant circuits, and for blocking DC voltages while passing AC signals, among numerous other uses.
[src:electronic-component/electronic-component] Integrated passive devices are passive devices integrated within one distinct package.
[src:electronic-component/electronic-component] They take up less space than equivalent combinations of discrete components.
[src:electronic-component/electronic-component] Electrical components that pass charge in proportion to magnetism or magnetic flux, and have the ability to retain a previous resistive state, hence the name of Memory plus Resistor.
[src:electronic-component/electronic-component] Sensors (detectors) are transducers that react to environmental conditions by changing their electrical properties or generating an electrical signal.
[src:electronic-component/electronic-component] The transducers listed here are single electronic components (as opposed to complete assemblies), and are passive (see Semiconductors and Tubes for active ones).
[src:electronic-component/electronic-component] Only the most common ones are listed here.
[src:electronic-component/electronic-component] On a circuit diagram, electronic devices are represented by conventional symbols.
[src:electronic-component/electronic-component] Reference designators are applied to the symbols to identify the components.
